# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: virology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:virology/bacteriophage] A **bacteriophage** (/bækˈtɪrioʊfeɪdʒ/), also known informally as a **phage** (/ˈfeɪdʒ/), is a virus that infects and replicates within bacteria.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The term is derived from Ancient Greek φαγεῖν*(phagein)* 'to devour' and *bacteria*.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are composed of proteins that encapsulate a DNA or RNA genome, and may have structures that are either simple or elaborate.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Their genomes may encode as few as four genes (e.g.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Phages replicate within the bacterium following the injection of their genome into its cytoplasm.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are among the most common and diverse entities in the biosphere.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are ubiquitous viruses, found wherever bacteria exist.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] It is estimated there are more than 1031 bacteriophages on the planet, more than every living organism on Earth, including bacteria, combined.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages were used from the 1920s as an alternative to antibiotics in the Soviet Union and Central Europe, as well as in France and Brazil.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] They are seen as a possible therapy against multi-drug-resistant strains of many bacteria.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are known to interact with the immune system both indirectly via bacterial expression of phage-encoded proteins and directly by influencing innate immunity and bacterial clearance.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Phage–host interactions are becoming increasingly important areas of research.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In 1896, Ernest Hanbury Hankin reported that something in the waters of the Ganges and Yamuna rivers in India had a marked antibacterial action against cholera and it could pass through a very fine porcelain Chamberland filter.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In 1915, British bacteriologist Frederick Twort, superintendent of the Brown Institution of London, discovered a small agent that infected and killed bacteria.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Twort's research was interrupted by the onset of World War I, as well as a shortage of funding and the discoveries of antibiotics.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Independently, French-Canadian microbiologist Félix d'Hérelle, working at the Pasteur Institute in Paris, announced on 3 September 1917 that he had discovered "an invisible, antagonistic microbe of the dysentery bacillus".
[src:virology/bacteriophage] He also recorded a dramatic account of a man suffering from dysentery who was restored to good health by the bacteriophages.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] It was d'Hérelle who conducted much research into bacteriophages and introduced the concept of phage therapy.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In 1919, in Paris, France, d'Hérelle conducted the first clinical application of a bacteriophage, with the first reported use in the United States being in 1922.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In 1969, Max Delbrück, Alfred Hershey, and Salvador Luria were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries of the replication of viruses and their genetic structure.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Specifically the work of Hershey, as contributor to the Hershey–Chase experiment in 1952, provided convincing evidence that DNA, not protein, was the genetic material of life.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Delbrück and Luria carried out the Luria–Delbrück experiment which demonstrated statistically that mutations in bacteria occur randomly and thus follow Darwinian rather than Lamarckian principles.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In 2018, George Smith and Gregory Winter were awarded Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the phage display of peptides and antibodies.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Phages were discovered to be antibacterial agents and were used in the former Soviet Republic of Georgia (pioneered there by Giorgi Eliava with help from the co-discoverer of bacteriophages, Félix d'Hérelle) during the 1920s and 1930s for treating bacterial infections.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] They had widespread use, including treatment of soldiers in the Red Army.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The use of phages has continued since the end of the Cold War in Russia, Georgia, and elsewhere in Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The first regulated, randomized, double-blind clinical trial was reported in the *Journal of Wound Care* in June 2009, which evaluated the safety and efficacy of a bacteriophage cocktail to treat infected venous ulcers of the leg in human patients.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The FDA approved the study as a Phase I clinical trial.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The study's results demonstrated the safety of therapeutic application of bacteriophages, but did not show efficacy.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The authors explained that the use of certain chemicals that are part of standard wound care (e.g. lactoferrin or silver) may have interfered with bacteriophage viability.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Shortly after that, another controlled clinical trial in Western Europe (treatment of ear infections caused by *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*) was reported in the journal *Clinical Otolaryngology* in August 2009.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The study concludes that bacteriophage preparations were safe and effective for treatment of chronic ear infections in humans.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Additionally, there have been numerous animal and other experimental clinical trials evaluating the efficacy of bacteriophages for various diseases, such as infected burns and wounds, and cystic fibrosis-associated lung infections, among others.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] On the other hand, phages of *Inoviridae* have been shown to complicate biofilms involved in pneumonia and cystic fibrosis and to shelter the bacteria from drugs meant to eradicate disease, thus promoting persistent infection.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Meanwhile, bacteriophage researchers have been developing engineered viruses to overcome antibiotic resistance, and engineering the phage genes responsible for coding enzymes that degrade the biofilm matrix, phage structural proteins, and the enzymes responsible for lysis of the bacterial cell wall.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] There have been results showing that T4 phages that are small in size and short-tailed can be helpful in detecting *E. coli* in the human body.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Therapeutic efficacy of a phage cocktail was evaluated in a mouse model with nasal infection of multi-drug-resistant (MDR) *A. baumannii*.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Mice treated with the phage cocktail showed a 2.3-fold higher survival rate compared to those untreated at seven days post-infection.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In 2017, a 68-year-old diabetic patient with necrotizing pancreatitis complicated by a pseudocyst infected with MDR *A. baumannii* strains was being treated with a cocktail of Azithromycin, Rifampicin, and Colistin for 4 months without results and overall rapidly declining health.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Once on the combination of the IV and PC therapy the patient's downward clinical trajectory reversed, and within two days he had awoken from his coma and become responsive.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] As his immune system began to function he had to be temporarily removed from the cocktail because his fever was spiking to over 104 °F (40 °C), but after two days the phage cocktails were re-introduced at levels he was able to tolerate.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The original three-antibiotic cocktail was replaced by minocycline after the bacterial strain was found not to be resistant to this and he rapidly regained full lucidity, although he was not discharged from the hospital until roughly 145 days after phage therapy began.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Phages have increasingly been used to safen food products and to forestall spoilage bacteria.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Since 2006, the United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) have approved several bacteriophage products.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] LMP-102 (Intralytix) was approved for treating ready-to-eat (RTE) poultry and meat products.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In that same year, the FDA approved LISTEX (developed and produced by Micreos) using bacteriophages on cheese to kill *Listeria monocytogenes* bacteria, in order to give them generally recognized as safe (GRAS) status.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In July 2007, the same bacteriophage were approved for use on all food products.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In 2011 USDA confirmed that LISTEX is a clean label processing aid and is included in USDA.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Research in the field of food safety is continuing to see if lytic phages are a viable option to control other food-borne pathogens in various food products.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Switzerland authorized a phage for use in cheese production in 2016.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The European Union has not yet (2025) authorized any.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages, including those specific to *Escherichia coli*, have been employed as indicators of fecal contamination in water sources.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Due to their shared structural and biological characteristics, coliphages can serve as proxies for viral fecal contamination and the presence of pathogenic viruses such as rotavirus, norovirus, and HAV.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Research conducted on wastewater treatment systems has revealed significant disparities in the behavior of coliphages compared to fecal coliforms, demonstrating a distinct correlation with the recovery of pathogenic viruses at the treatment's conclusion.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Establishing a secure discharge threshold, studies have determined that discharges below 3000 PFU/100 mL are considered safe in terms of limiting the release of pathogenic viruses.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In 2011, the FDA cleared the first bacteriophage-based product for in vitro diagnostic use.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The KeyPath MRSA/MSSA Blood Culture Test uses a cocktail of bacteriophage to detect *Staphylococcus aureus* in positive blood cultures and determine methicillin resistance or susceptibility.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The test returns results in about five hours, compared to two to three days for standard microbial identification and susceptibility test methods.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] It was the first accelerated antibiotic-susceptibility test approved by the FDA.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Government agencies in the West have for several years been looking to Georgia and the former Soviet Union for help with exploiting phages for counteracting bioweapons and toxins, such as anthrax and botulism.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Developments are continuing among research groups in the U.S.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Other uses include spray application in horticulture for protecting plants and vegetable produce from decay and the spread of bacterial disease.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Other applications for bacteriophages are as biocides for environmental surfaces, e.g., in hospitals, and as preventative treatments for catheters and medical devices before use in clinical settings.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The technology for phages to be applied to dry surfaces, e.g., uniforms, curtains, or even sutures for surgery now exists.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Clinical trials reported in *Clinical Otolaryngology* show success in veterinary treatment of pet dogs with otitis.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The sensing of phage-triggered ion cascades (SEPTIC) bacterium sensing and identification method uses the ion emission and its dynamics during phage infection and offers high specificity and speed for detection.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Phage display is a different use of phages involving a library of phages with a variable peptide linked to a surface protein.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Each phage genome encodes the variant of the protein displayed on its surface (hence the name), providing a link between the peptide variant and its encoding gene.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Variant phages from the library may be selected through their binding affinity to an immobilized molecule (e.g., botulism toxin) to neutralize it.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The bound, selected phages can be multiplied by reinfecting a susceptible bacterial strain, thus allowing them to retrieve the peptides encoded in them for further study.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Phage proteins often have antimicrobial activity and may serve as leads for peptidomimetics, i.e. drugs that mimic peptides.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Phage-ligand technology makes use of phage proteins for various applications, such as binding of bacteria and bacterial components (e.g. endotoxin) and lysis of bacteria.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are important model organisms for studying principles of evolution and ecology.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Phages can be used to combat bacterial infections such as blackleg.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] A line of phage-based products is licensed in the United States, and Georgia has long used agricultural phages.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Elsewhere, research and pilot testing are still underway.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] This is notably the case in Switzerland, where research is being conducted by the Fribourg School of Engineering and Architecture in collaboration with the Lausanne University Hospital (CHUV).
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages present in the environment can cause cheese to not ferment.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In order to avoid this, mixed-strain starter cultures and culture rotation regimes can be used.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Genetic engineering of culture microbes – especially *Lactococcus lactis* and *Streptococcus thermophilus* – have been studied for genetic analysis and modification to improve phage resistance.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] This has especially focused on plasmid and recombinant chromosomal modifications.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Some research has focused on the potential of bacteriophages as antimicrobial against foodborne pathogens and biofilm formation within the dairy industry.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] As the spread of antibiotic resistance is a main concern within the dairy industry, phages can serve as a promising alternative.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The life cycle of bacteriophages tends to be either a lytic cycle or a lysogenic cycle.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In addition, some phages display pseudolysogenic behaviors.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] With *lytic phages* such as the T4 phage, bacterial cells are broken open (lysed) and destroyed after immediate replication of the virion.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] As soon as the cell is destroyed, the phage progeny can find new hosts to infect.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Lytic phages are more suitable for phage therapy.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Some lytic phages undergo a phenomenon known as lysis inhibition, where completed phage progeny will not immediately lyse out of the cell if extracellular phage concentrations are high.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] This mechanism is not identical to that of the temperate phage going dormant and usually is temporary.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In contrast, the *lysogenic cycle* does not result in immediate lysing of the host cell.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Those phages able to undergo lysogeny are known as temperate phages.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Their viral genome will integrate with host DNA and replicate along with it, relatively harmlessly, or may even become established as a plasmid.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The virus remains dormant until host conditions deteriorate, perhaps due to depletion of nutrients, then, the endogenous phages (known as prophages) become active.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] At this point they initiate the reproductive cycle, resulting in lysis of the host cell.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] As the lysogenic cycle allows the host cell to continue to survive and reproduce, the virus is replicated in all offspring of the cell.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Sometimes prophages may provide benefits to the host bacterium while they are dormant by adding new functions to the bacterial genome, in a phenomenon called lysogenic conversion.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Examples are the conversion of harmless strains of *Corynebacterium diphtheriae* or *Vibrio cholerae* by bacteriophages to highly virulent ones that cause diphtheria or cholera, respectively.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Strategies to combat certain bacterial infections by targeting these toxin-encoding prophages have been proposed.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacterial cells are protected by a cell wall of polysaccharides, which are important virulence factors protecting bacterial cells against both immune host defenses and antibiotics.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] To enter a host cell, bacteriophages bind to specific receptors on the surface of bacteria, including lipopolysaccharides, teichoic acids, proteins, or even flagella.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] This specificity means a bacteriophage can infect only certain bacteria bearing receptors to which they can bind, which in turn, determines the phage's host range.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Polysaccharide-degrading enzymes are virion-associated proteins that enzymatically degrade the capsular outer layer of their hosts at the initial step of a tightly programmed phage infection process.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Host growth conditions also influence the ability of the phage to attach and invade them.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] As phage virions do not move independently, they must rely on random encounters with the correct receptors when in solution, such as blood, lymphatic circulation, irrigation, soil water, etc.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Myovirus bacteriophages use a hypodermic syringe-like motion to inject their genetic material into the cell.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] After contacting the appropriate receptor, the tail fibers flex to bring the base plate closer to the surface of the cell.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Once attached completely, irreversible binding is initiated and the tail contracts, possibly with the help of ATP present in the tail, injecting genetic material through the bacterial membrane.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The injection is accomplished through a sort of bending motion in the shaft by going to the side, contracting closer to the cell and pushing back up.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Podoviruses lack an elongated tail sheath like that of a myovirus, so instead, they use their small, tooth-like tail fibers enzymatically to degrade a portion of the cell membrane before inserting their genetic material.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Within minutes, bacterial ribosomes start translating viral mRNA into protein.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] For RNA-based phages, RNA replicase is synthesized early in the process.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Proteins modify the bacterial RNA polymerase so it preferentially transcribes viral mRNA.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The host's normal synthesis of proteins and nucleic acids is disrupted, and it is forced to manufacture viral products instead.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] These products go on to become part of new virions within the cell, helper proteins that contribute to the assemblage of new virions, or proteins involved in cell lysis.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In 1972, Walter Fiers (University of Ghent, Belgium) was the first to establish the complete nucleotide sequence of a gene and in 1976, of the viral genome of bacteriophage MS2.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Some dsDNA bacteriophages encode ribosomal proteins, which are thought to modulate protein translation during phage infection.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In the case of the T4 phage, the construction of new virus particles involves the assistance of helper proteins that act catalytically during phage morphogenesis.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The base plates are assembled first, with the tails being built upon them afterward.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The head capsids, constructed separately, will spontaneously assemble with the tails.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] During assembly of the phage T4 virion, the morphogenetic proteins encoded by the phage genes interact with each other in a characteristic sequence.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Maintaining an appropriate balance in the amounts of each of these proteins produced during viral infection appears to be critical for normal phage T4 morphogenesis.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The DNA is packed efficiently within the heads.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The whole process takes about 15 minutes.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Early studies of bacteriophage T4 (1962–1964) provided an opportunity to gain understanding of virtually all of the genes that are essential for growth of the bacteriophage under laboratory conditions.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] These studies were made possible by the availability of two classes of conditional lethal mutants.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] One class of such mutants was referred to as amber mutants.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The other class of conditional lethal mutants was referred to as temperature-sensitive mutants.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Studies of these two classes of mutants led to considerable insight into the functions and interactions of the proteins employed in the machinery of DNA replication, repair and recombination, and on how viruses are assembled from protein and nucleic acid components (molecular morphogenesis).
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Phages may be released via cell lysis, by extrusion, or, in a few cases, by budding.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Lysis, by tailed phages, is achieved by an enzyme called endolysin, which attacks and breaks down the cell wall peptidoglycan.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] An altogether different phage type, the filamentous phage, makes the host cell continually secrete new virus particles.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Released virions are described as free, and, unless defective, are capable of infecting a new bacterium.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Budding is associated with certain *Mycoplasma* phages.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In contrast to virion release, phages displaying a lysogenic cycle do not kill the host and instead become long-term residents as prophages.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Research in 2017 revealed that the bacteriophage Φ3T makes a short viral protein that signals other bacteriophages to lie dormant instead of killing the host bacterium.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Arbitrium is the name given to this protein by the researchers who discovered it.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Given the millions of different phages in the environment, phage genomes come in a variety of forms and sizes.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] RNA phages such as MS2 have the smallest genomes, with only a few kilobases.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] However, some DNA phages such as T4 may have large genomes with hundreds of genes; the size and shape of the capsid varies along with the size of the genome.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The largest bacteriophage genomes reach a size of 735 kb.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophage genomes can be highly mosaic, i.e. the genome of many phage species appear to be composed of numerous individual modules.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] These modules may be found in other phage species in different arrangements.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Mycobacteriophages, bacteriophages with mycobacterial hosts, have provided excellent examples of this mosaicism.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In these mycobacteriophages, genetic assortment may be the result of repeated instances of site-specific recombination and illegitimate recombination (the result of phage genome acquisition of bacterial host genetic sequences).
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Evolutionary mechanisms shaping the genomes of bacterial viruses vary between different families and depend upon the type of the nucleic acid, characteristics of the virion structure, as well as the mode of the viral life cycle.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Some marine roseobacter phages, also known as roseophages, contain deoxyuridine (dU) instead of deoxythymidine (dT) in their genomic DNA.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] There is some evidence that this unusual component is a mechanism to evade bacterial defense mechanisms such as restriction endonucleases and CRISPR/Cas systems which evolved to recognize and cleave sequences within invading phages, thereby inactivating them.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Other phages have long been known to use unusual nucleotides.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] In 1963, Takahashi and Marmur identified a *Bacillus* phage that has dU substituting dT in its genome, and in 1977, Kirnos et al. identified a cyanophage containing 2-aminoadenine (Z) instead of adenine (A).
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The field of systems biology investigates the complex networks of interactions within an organism, usually using computational tools and modeling.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] For example, a phage genome that enters into a bacterial host cell may express hundreds of phage proteins which will affect the expression of numerous host genes or the host's metabolism.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] All of these complex interactions can be described and simulated in computer models.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] For instance, infection of *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* by the temperate phage PaP3 changed the expression of 38% (2160/5633) of its host's genes.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Many of these effects are probably indirect, hence the challenge becomes to identify the direct interactions among bacteria and phage.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Several attempts have been made to map protein–protein interactions among phage and their host.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] For instance, bacteriophage lambda was found to interact with its host, *E. coli*, by dozens of interactions.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Again, the significance of many of these interactions remains unclear, but these studies suggest that there most likely are several key interactions and many indirect interactions whose role remains uncharacterized.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are a major threat to bacteria and prokaryotes, which have evolved numerous mechanisms to block infection (host resistance) or to block the replication of bacteriophages within host cells (anti-phage defense).
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Temperate phages are bacteriophages that integrate their genetic material into the host as extrachromosomal episomes or as a prophage during a lysogenic cycle.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophage–host symbiosis may benefit bacteria by providing selective advantages while passively replicating the phage genome.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Metagenomics has allowed the in-water detection of bacteriophages that was not possible previously.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Also, bacteriophages have been used in hydrological tracing and modelling in river systems, especially where surface water and groundwater interactions occur.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The use of phages is preferred to the more conventional dye marker because they are significantly less absorbed when passing through ground waters and they are readily detected at very low concentrations.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Non-polluted water may contain approximately 2×108 bacteriophages per ml.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are thought to contribute extensively to horizontal gene transfer in natural environments, principally via transduction, but also via transformation.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Metagenomics-based studies also have revealed that viromes from a variety of environments harbor antibiotic-resistance genes, including those that could confer multidrug resistance.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Recent findings have mapped the complex and intertwined arsenal of anti-phage defense tools in environmental bacteria.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Although phages do not infect humans, there are countless phage particles in the human body, given the extensive human microbiome.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] One's phage population has been called the human phageome, including the "healthy gut phageome" (HGP) and the "diseased human phageome" (DHP).
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The active phageome of a healthy human (i.e., actively replicating as opposed to nonreplicating, integrated prophage) has been estimated to comprise dozens to thousands of different viruses.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] There is evidence that bacteriophages and bacteria interact in the human gut microbiome both antagonistically and beneficially.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Preliminary studies have indicated that common bacteriophages are found in 62% of healthy individuals on average, while their prevalence was reduced by 42% and 54% on average in patients with ulcerative colitis (UC) and Crohn's disease (CD).
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Abundance of phages may also decline in the elderly.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] The most common phages in the human intestine, found worldwide, are crAssphages.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] CrAssphages are transmitted from mother to child soon after birth, and there is some evidence suggesting that they may be transmitted locally.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Each person develops their own unique crAssphage clusters.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] CrAss-like phages also may be present in primates besides humans.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] Among the countless phages, only a few have been studied in detail, including some historically important phages that were discovered in the early days of microbial genetics.
[src:virology/bacteriophage] These, especially the T-phage, helped to discover important principles of gene structure and function.
[src:virology/capsid] A **capsid** is the protein shell of a virus, enclosing its genetic material.
[src:virology/capsid] It consists of several oligomeric (repeating) structural subunits made of protein called protomers.
[src:virology/capsid] The observable 3-dimensional morphological subunits, which may or may not correspond to individual proteins, are called capsomeres.
[src:virology/capsid] The proteins making up the capsid are called **capsid proteins** or **viral coat proteins** (**VCP**).
[src:virology/capsid] The virus genomic component inside the capsid, along with occasionally present virus core protein, is called the **virus core**.
[src:virology/capsid] The capsid and core together are referred to as a **nucleocapsid** (cf. also virion).
[src:virology/capsid] Capsids are broadly classified according to their structure.
[src:virology/capsid] The majority of the viruses have capsids with either helical or icosahedral structure.
[src:virology/capsid] Some viruses, such as bacteriophages, have developed more complicated structures due to constraints of elasticity and electrostatics.
[src:virology/capsid] The icosahedral shape, which has 20 equilateral triangular faces, approximates a sphere, while the helical shape resembles the shape of a spring, taking the space of a cylinder but not being a cylinder itself.
[src:virology/capsid] The capsid faces may consist of one or more proteins.
[src:virology/capsid] For example, the foot-and-mouth disease virus capsid has faces consisting of three proteins named VP1–3.
[src:virology/capsid] Some viruses are *enveloped*, meaning that the capsid is coated with a lipid membrane known as the viral envelope.
[src:virology/capsid] The envelope is acquired by the capsid from an intracellular membrane in the virus' host; examples include the inner nuclear membrane, the Golgi membrane, and the cell's outer membrane.
[src:virology/capsid] Once the virus has infected a cell and begins replicating itself, new capsid subunits are synthesized using the protein biosynthesis mechanism of the cell.
[src:virology/capsid] In some viruses, including those with helical capsids and especially those with RNA genomes, the capsid proteins co-assemble with their genomes.
[src:virology/capsid] In other viruses, especially more complex viruses with double-stranded DNA genomes, the capsid proteins assemble into empty precursor **procapsids** that include a specialized portal structure at one vertex.
[src:virology/capsid] Through this portal, viral DNA is translocated into the capsid.
[src:virology/capsid] Structural analyses of major capsid protein (MCP) architectures have been used to categorise viruses into lineages.
[src:virology/capsid] For example, the bacteriophage PRD1, the algal virus *Paramecium bursaria Chlorella virus-1* (PBCV-1), mimivirus and the mammalian adenovirus have been placed in the same lineage, whereas tailed, double-stranded DNA bacteriophages (*Caudovirales*) and herpesvirus belong to a second lineage.
[src:virology/capsid] The icosahedral structure is extremely common among viruses.
[src:virology/capsid] The icosahedron consists of 20 triangular faces delimited by 12 fivefold vertexes and consists of 60 asymmetric units.
[src:virology/capsid] Thus, an icosahedral virus is made of 60N protein subunits.
[src:virology/capsid] The number and arrangement of capsomeres in an icosahedral capsid can be classified using the "quasi-equivalence principle" proposed by Donald Caspar and Aaron Klug.
[src:virology/capsid] Like the Goldberg polyhedra, an icosahedral structure can be regarded as being constructed from pentamers and hexamers.
[src:virology/capsid] The structures can be indexed by two integers *h* and *k*, with $h\geq 1$ and $k\geq 0$ ; the structure can be thought of as taking *h* steps from the edge of a pentamer, turning 60 degrees counterclockwise, then taking *k* steps to get to the next pentamer.
[src:virology/capsid] In this scheme, icosahedral capsids contain 12 pentamers plus 10(*T* − 1) hexamers.
[src:virology/capsid] The *T*-number is representative of the size and complexity of the capsids.
[src:virology/capsid] Geometric examples for many values of *h*, *k*, and *T* can be found at List of geodesic polyhedra and Goldberg polyhedra.
[src:virology/capsid] Many exceptions to this rule exist: For example, the polyomaviruses and papillomaviruses have pentamers instead of hexamers in hexavalent positions on a quasi T = 7 lattice.
[src:virology/capsid] Members of the double-stranded RNA virus lineage, including reovirus, rotavirus and bacteriophage φ6 have capsids built of 120 copies of capsid protein, corresponding to a T = 2 capsid, or arguably a T = 1 capsid with a dimer in the asymmetric unit.
[src:virology/capsid] An elongated icosahedron is a common shape for the heads of bacteriophages.
[src:virology/capsid] Such a structure is composed of a cylinder with a cap at either end.
[src:virology/capsid] The cylinder is composed of 10 elongated triangular faces.
[src:virology/capsid] The Q number (or Tmid), which can be any positive integer, specifies the number of triangles, composed of asymmetric subunits, that make up the 10 triangles of the cylinder.
[src:virology/capsid] The caps are classified by the T (or Tend) number.
[src:virology/capsid] The bacterium *E. coli* is the host for bacteriophage T4 that has a prolate head structure.
[src:virology/capsid] The bacteriophage encoded gp31 protein appears to be functionally homologous to *E. coli* chaperone protein GroES and able to substitute for it in the assembly of bacteriophage T4 virions during infection.
[src:virology/capsid] Like GroES, gp31 forms a stable complex with GroEL chaperonin that is absolutely necessary for the folding and assembly *in vivo* of the bacteriophage T4 major capsid protein gp23.
[src:virology/capsid] Many rod-shaped and filamentous plant viruses have capsids with helical symmetry.
[src:virology/capsid] The helical structure can be described as a set of *n* 1-D molecular helices related by an *n*-fold axial symmetry.
[src:virology/capsid] The helical transformation are classified into two categories: one-dimensional and two-dimensional helical systems.
[src:virology/capsid] Creating an entire helical structure relies on a set of translational and rotational matrices which are coded in the protein data bank.
[src:virology/capsid] Helical symmetry is given by the formula *P* = *μ* x *ρ*, where *μ* is the number of structural units per turn of the helix, *ρ* is the axial rise per unit and *P* is the pitch of the helix.
[src:virology/capsid] The structure is said to be open due to the characteristic that any volume can be enclosed by varying the length of the helix.
[src:virology/capsid] The most understood helical virus is the tobacco mosaic virus.
[src:virology/capsid] The virus is a single molecule of (+) strand RNA.
[src:virology/capsid] Each coat protein on the interior of the helix binds three nucleotides of the RNA genome, with the overall polymer having a μ value of 16.33 protein subunits per helical turn.
[src:virology/capsid] Influenza A viruses differ by comprising multiple ribonucleoproteins which organize the segmented RNA into double helical structures.
[src:virology/capsid] The virus must assemble a stable, protective protein shell to protect the genome from lethal chemical and physical agents.
[src:virology/capsid] These include extremes of pH or temperature and proteolytic and nucleolytic enzymes.
[src:virology/capsid] For non-enveloped viruses, the capsid itself may be involved in interaction with receptors on the host cell, leading to penetration of the host cell membrane and internalization of the capsid.
[src:virology/capsid] Delivery of the genome occurs by subsequent uncoating or disassembly of the capsid and release of the genome into the cytoplasm, or by ejection of the genome through a specialized portal structure directly into the host cell nucleus.
[src:virology/capsid] It has been suggested that many viral capsid proteins have evolved on multiple occasions from functionally diverse cellular proteins.
[src:virology/capsid] As a result, some capsid proteins are widespread in viruses infecting distantly related organisms (e.g., capsid proteins with the jelly-roll fold), whereas others are restricted to a particular group of viruses (e.g., capsid proteins of alphaviruses).
[src:virology/capsid] The displacement of these ancestral genes between cellular organisms could favor the appearance of new viruses during evolution.
[src:virology/retrovirus] A **retrovirus** is a virus that inserts a DNA copy of its RNA genome into the DNA of a host cell that it invades, thus changing the genome of that cell.
[src:virology/retrovirus] After invading a host cell's cytoplasm, the virus uses its own reverse transcriptase enzyme to produce DNA from its RNA genome, the reverse of the usual pattern, thus *retro* (backward).
[src:virology/retrovirus] The new DNA is then incorporated into the host cell genome by an integrase enzyme, at which point the retroviral DNA is referred to as a provirus.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The host cell then treats the viral DNA as part of its own genome, transcribing and translating the viral genes along with the cell's own genes, producing the proteins required to assemble new copies of the virus.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Many retroviruses cause serious diseases in humans, other mammals, and birds.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Retroviruses have many subfamilies in three basic groups.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The specialized DNA-infiltration enzymes in retroviruses make them valuable research tools in molecular biology, and they have been used successfully in gene delivery systems.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Evidence from endogenous retroviruses (inherited provirus DNA in animal genomes) suggests that retroviruses have been infecting vertebrates for at least 450 million years.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Virions, viruses in the form of independent particles of retroviruses, consist of enveloped particles about 100 nm in diameter.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The outer lipid envelope consists of glycoprotein.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The virions also contain two identical single-stranded RNA molecules 7–10 kilobases in length.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The two molecules are present as a dimer, formed by base pairing between complementary sequences.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Interaction sites between the two RNA molecules have been identified as a "kissing stem-loop".
[src:virology/retrovirus] Although virions of different retroviruses do not have the same morphology or biology, all the virion components are very similar.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The retroviral genome is packaged as viral particles.
[src:virology/retrovirus] These viral particles are dimers of single-stranded, positive-sense, linear RNA molecules.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Retroviruses (and orterviruses in general) follow a layout of 5'–*gag*–*pro*–*pol*–*env*–3' in the RNA genome.
[src:virology/retrovirus] *gag* and *pol* encode polyproteins, each managing the capsid and replication.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The *pol* region encodes enzymes necessary for viral replication, such as reverse transcriptase, protease and integrase.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Depending on the virus, the genes may overlap or fuse into larger polyprotein chains.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The lentivirus genus, the spumavirus genus, the HTLV / bovine leukemia virus (BLV) genus, and a newly introduced fish virus genus are retroviruses classified as complex.
[src:virology/retrovirus] These viruses have genes called accessory genes, in addition to gag, pro, pol and env genes.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Accessory genes are located between pol and env, downstream from the env, including the U3 region of LTR, or in the env and overlapping portions.
[src:virology/retrovirus] While accessory genes have auxiliary roles, they also coordinate and regulate viral gene expression.
[src:virology/retrovirus] In addition, some retroviruses may carry genes called oncogenes or onc genes from another class.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Retroviruses with these genes (also called transforming viruses) are known for their ability to quickly cause tumors in animals and transform cells in culture into an oncogenic state.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The polyproteins are cleaved into smaller proteins each with their own function.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The nucleotides encoding them are known as *subgenes*.
[src:virology/retrovirus] When retroviruses have integrated their own genome into the germ line, their genome is passed on to a following generation.
[src:virology/retrovirus] These endogenous retroviruses (ERVs), contrasted with exogenous ones, now make up 5–8% of the human genome.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Most insertions have no known function and are often referred to as "junk DNA".
[src:virology/retrovirus] However, many endogenous retroviruses play important roles in host biology, such as control of gene transcription, cell fusion during placental development in the course of the germination of an embryo, and resistance to exogenous retroviral infection.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Endogenous retroviruses have also received special attention in the research of immunology-related pathologies, such as autoimmune diseases like multiple sclerosis, although endogenous retroviruses have not yet been proven to play any causal role in this class of disease.
[src:virology/retrovirus] While transcription was classically thought to occur only from DNA to RNA, reverse transcriptase transcribes RNA into DNA.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The term "retro" in retrovirus refers to this reversal (making DNA from RNA) of the usual direction of transcription.
[src:virology/retrovirus] It still obeys the central dogma of molecular biology, which states that information can be transferred from nucleic acid to nucleic acid but cannot be transferred back from protein to either protein or nucleic acid.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Reverse transcriptase activity outside of retroviruses has been found in almost all eukaryotes, enabling the generation and insertion of new copies of retrotransposons into the host genome.
[src:virology/retrovirus] These inserts are transcribed by enzymes of the host into new RNA molecules that enter the cytosol.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Next, some of these RNA molecules are translated into viral proteins.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The proteins encoded by the gag and pol genes are translated from genome-length mRNAs into Gag and Gag–Pol polyproteins.
[src:virology/retrovirus] In example, for the *gag* gene; it is translated into molecules of the capsid protein, and for the *pol* gene; it is translated into molecules of reverse transcriptase.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Retroviruses need a lot more of the Gag proteins than the Pol proteins and have developed advanced systems to synthesize the required amount of each.
[src:virology/retrovirus] As an example, after Gag synthesis nearly 95 percent of the ribosomes terminate translation, while other ribosomes continue translation to synthesize Gag–Pol.
[src:virology/retrovirus] In the rough endoplasmic reticulum glycosylation begins and the *env* gene is translated from spliced mRNAs in the rough endoplasmic reticulum, into molecules of the envelope protein.
[src:virology/retrovirus] When the envelope protein molecules are carried to the Golgi complex, they are divided into surface glycoprotein and transmembrane glycoprotein by a host protease.
[src:virology/retrovirus] These two glycoprotein products stay in close affiliation, and they are transported to the plasma membrane after further glycosylation.
[src:virology/retrovirus] A retrovirus must "bring" its own reverse transcriptase in its capsid, otherwise it is unable to utilize the enzymes of the infected cell to carry out the task, due to the unusual nature of producing DNA from RNA.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Industrial drugs that are designed as protease and reverse-transcriptase inhibitors are made such that they target specific sites and sequences within their respective enzymes.
[src:virology/retrovirus] However these drugs can quickly become ineffective due to the fact that the gene sequences that code for the protease and the reverse transcriptase quickly mutate.
[src:virology/retrovirus] These changes in bases cause specific codons and sites with the enzymes to change and thereby avoid drug targeting by losing the sites that the drug actually targets.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Because reverse transcription lacks the usual proofreading of DNA replication, a retrovirus mutates very often.
[src:virology/retrovirus] This enables the virus to grow resistant to antiviral pharmaceuticals quickly, and impedes the development of effective vaccines and inhibitors for the retrovirus.
[src:virology/retrovirus] One difficulty faced with some retroviruses, such as the Moloney retrovirus, involves the requirement for cells to be actively dividing for transduction.
[src:virology/retrovirus] As a result, cells such as neurons are very resistant to infection and transduction by retroviruses.
[src:virology/retrovirus] This gives rise to a concern that insertional mutagenesis due to integration into the host genome might lead to cancer or leukemia.
[src:virology/retrovirus] This is unlike *Lentivirus*, a genus of *Retroviridae*, which are able to integrate their RNA into the genome of non-dividing host cells.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Two RNA genomes are packaged into each retrovirus particle, but, after an infection, each virus generates only one provirus.
[src:virology/retrovirus] After infection, reverse transcription occurs and this process is accompanied by recombination.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Recombination involves template strand switching between the two genome copies (copy choice recombination) during reverse transcription.
[src:virology/retrovirus] From 5 to 14 recombination events per genome occur at each replication cycle.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Genetic recombination appears to be necessary for maintaining genome integrity and as a repair mechanism for salvaging damaged genomes.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The DNA formed after reverse transcription (the provirus) is longer than the RNA genome because each of the terminals have the U3 - R - U5 sequences called long terminal repeat (LTR).
[src:virology/retrovirus] Thus, 5' terminal has the extra U3 sequence, while the other terminal has the U5 sequence.
[src:virology/retrovirus] LTRs are able to send signals for vital tasks to be carried out such as initiation of RNA production or management of the rate of transcription.
[src:virology/retrovirus] This way, LTRs can control replication, hence, the entire progress of the viral cycle.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Although located in the nucleus, the non-integrated retroviral cDNA is a very weak substrate for transcription.
[src:virology/retrovirus] For this reason, an integrated provirus is a necessary for permanent and an effective expression of retroviral genes.
[src:virology/retrovirus] This DNA can be incorporated into host genome as a provirus that can be passed on to progeny cells.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The retrovirus DNA is inserted at random into the host genome.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Because of this, it can be inserted into oncogenes.
[src:virology/retrovirus] In this way some retroviruses can convert normal cells into cancer cells.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Some provirus remains latent in the cell for a long period of time before it is activated by the change in cell environment.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Studies of retroviruses led to the first demonstrated synthesis of DNA from RNA templates, a fundamental mode for transferring genetic material that occurs in both eukaryotes and prokaryotes.
[src:virology/retrovirus] It has been speculated that the RNA to DNA transcription processes used by retroviruses may have first caused DNA to be used as genetic material.
[src:virology/retrovirus] In this model, the RNA world hypothesis, cellular organisms adopted the more chemically stable DNA when retroviruses evolved to create DNA from the RNA templates.
[src:virology/retrovirus] An estimate of the date of evolution of the foamy-like endogenous retroviruses placed the time of the most recent common ancestor at > 450 million years ago.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Gammaretroviral and lentiviral vectors for gene therapy have been developed that mediate stable genetic modification of treated cells by chromosomal integration of the transferred vector genomes.
[src:virology/retrovirus] This technology is of use, not only for research purposes, but also for clinical gene therapy aiming at the long-term correction of genetic defects, e.g., in stem and progenitor cells.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Retroviral vector particles with tropism for various target cells have been designed.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Gammaretroviral and lentiviral vectors have so far been used in more than 300 clinical trials, addressing treatment options for various diseases.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Retroviral mutations can be developed to make transgenic mouse models to study various cancers and their metastatic models.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Retroviruses that cause tumor growth include Rous sarcoma virus and mouse mammary tumor virus.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Cancer can be triggered by proto-oncogenes that were mistakenly incorporated into proviral DNA or by the disruption of cellular proto-oncogenes.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Rous sarcoma virus contains the src gene that triggers tumor formation.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Later it was found that a similar gene in cells is involved in cell signaling, which was most likely excised with the proviral DNA.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Nontransforming viruses can randomly insert their DNA into proto-oncogenes, disrupting the expression of proteins that regulate the cell cycle.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The promoter of the provirus DNA can also cause over expression of regulatory genes.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Retroviruses can cause diseases such as cancer and immunodeficiency.
[src:virology/retrovirus] If viral DNA is integrated into host chromosomes, it can lead to permanent infections.
[src:virology/retrovirus] It is therefore important to discover the body's response to retroviruses.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Exogenous retroviruses are especially associated with pathogenic diseases.
[src:virology/retrovirus] For example, mice have mouse mammary tumor virus (MMTV), which is a retrovirus.
[src:virology/retrovirus] This virus passes to newborn mice through mammary milk.
[src:virology/retrovirus] When they are 6 months old, the mice carrying the virus get mammary cancer because of the retrovirus.
[src:virology/retrovirus] In addition, leukemia virus I (HTLV-1), found in human T cell, has been found in humans for many years.
[src:virology/retrovirus] It is estimated that this retrovirus causes leukemia in the ages of 40 and 50.
[src:virology/retrovirus] It has a replicable structure that can induce cancer.
[src:virology/retrovirus] In addition to the usual gene sequence of retroviruses, HTLV-1 contains a fourth region, PX.
[src:virology/retrovirus] This region encodes Tax, Rex, p12, p13 and p30 regulatory proteins.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The Tax protein initiates the leukemic process and organizes the transcription of all viral genes in the integrated HTLV proviral DNA.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Exogenous retroviruses are infectious RNA- or DNA-containing viruses that are transmitted from one organism to another.
[src:virology/retrovirus] All members of Group VI use virally encoded reverse transcriptase, an RNA-dependent DNA polymerase, to produce DNA from the initial virion RNA genome.
[src:virology/retrovirus] This DNA is often integrated into the host genome, as in the case of retroviruses and pseudoviruses, where it is replicated and transcribed by the host.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The family *Retroviridae* was previously divided into three subfamilies (*Oncovirinae*, *Lentivirinae*, and *Spumavirinae*), but are now divided into two: *Orthoretrovirinae* and *Spumaretrovirinae*.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The term oncovirus is now commonly used to describe a cancer-causing virus.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Both families in Group VII have DNA genomes contained within the invading virus particles.
[src:virology/retrovirus] The DNA genome is transcribed into both mRNA, for use as a transcript in protein synthesis, and pre-genomic RNA, for use as the template during genome replication.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Virally encoded reverse transcriptase uses the pre-genomic RNA as a template for the creation of genomic DNA.
[src:virology/retrovirus] whilst families *Belpaoviridae*, *Metaviridae*, *Pseudoviridae*, *Retroviridae*, and *Caulimoviridae* constitute the order *Ortervirales*.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Antiretroviral drugs are medications for the treatment of infection by retroviruses, primarily HIV.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Different classes of antiretroviral drugs act on different stages of the HIV life cycle.
[src:virology/retrovirus] Combination of several (typically three or four) antiretroviral drugs is known as highly active antiretroviral therapy (HAART).
[src:virology/retrovirus] Feline leukemia virus and Feline immunodeficiency virus infections are treated with biologics, including the only immunomodulator currently licensed for sale in the United States, Lymphocyte T-Cell Immune Modulator (LTCI).
[src:virology/viral-envelope] A **viral envelope** is the outermost layer of many types of viruses.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] It protects the genetic material in their life cycle when traveling between host cells.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] A **viral envelope protein** or **E protein** is a protein in the envelope, which may be acquired by the capsid from an infected host cell.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Numerous human pathogenic viruses in circulation are encased in lipid bilayers, and they infect their target cells by causing the viral envelope and cell membrane to fuse.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Although there are effective vaccines against some of these viruses, there is no preventative or curative medicine for the majority of them.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] In most cases, the known vaccines operate by inducing antibodies that prevent the pathogen from entering cells.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] This happens in the case of enveloped viruses when the antibodies bind to the viral envelope proteins.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The membrane fusion event that triggers viral entrance is caused by the viral membrane fusion protein.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Many enveloped viruses only have one protein visible on the surface of the particle, which is required for both mediating adhesion to the cell surface and for the subsequent membrane fusion process.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Enveloped viruses enter cells by joining a cellular membrane to their lipid bilayer membrane.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Priming by proteolytic processing, either of the fusion protein or of a companion protein, is necessary for the majority of viral fusion proteins.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The priming stage then gets the fusion protein ready for triggering by the processes that go along with attachment and uptake, which frequently happens during transport of the fusion protein to the cell surface but may also happen extracellularly.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] So far, structural studies have revealed two kinds of viral fusion proteins.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] These proteins are believed to catalyze the same mechanism in both situations, resulting in the fusing of two bilayers.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] In other words, these proteins operate as enzymes, which while having various structural variations catalyze the same chemical reaction.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The envelopes are typically derived from portions of the host cell membranes (phospholipids and proteins), but include some viral glycoproteins.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] One of the main parts of human pathogenic viruses is glycoprotein.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] They have been shown to play significant roles in immunity and infection.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Viral glycoproteins, a new class of cellular inhibitory proteins has been discovered.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] These include the E3 ubiquitin ligases of the membrane-associated RING-CH (MARCH) family, which among other things, inhibits the expression of cell surface proteins implicated in adaptive immunity.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Being made up mostly of host membrane, the viral envelope can also have the proteins associated with the host cell within their membrane after budding.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Many enveloped viruses mature by budding at the plasma membrane, which allows them to be discharged from infected cells.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] During this procedure, viral transmembrane proteins, also known as spike proteins, are integrated into membrane vesicles containing components of the viral core (capsid).
[src:virology/viral-envelope] For a very long time, it was thought that the spike proteins, which are necessary for infectivity, were directly incorporated into the viral core through their cytoplasmic domains.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Recent research suggests that while such direct interactions may be what causes the budding of alphaviruses, this may not be the case for retroviruses and negative strand RNA viruses.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] These viruses can form bud particles even in the absence of spike proteins by relying only on viral core components.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The spike proteins can occasionally be produced as virus-like particles without the viral core.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Therefore, optimal budding and release may be dependent on a coordinated "push-and-pull" action between core and spike, where oligomerization of both components is essential.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Envelopes may help viruses avoid the host immune system.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] TAM receptor tyrosine kinases increase phagocytic clearance of apoptotic cells and inhibit immunological responses brought on by Toll-like receptors and type I interferons (IFNs) when they are activated by the ligands Gas6 and Protein S.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The phospholipid phosphatidylserine may be seen on the membranes of several enveloped viruses, which they employ to bind Gas6 and Protein S to activate TAM receptors.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] As a result, flaviviruses and pseudo typed retroviruses have a harder time infecting TAM-deficient DCs, albeit infection can be brought back by type I IFN antibodies.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] A TAM kinase inhibitor, meanwhile, prevents infection of wild-type DCs.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] TAM receptors, which are potential targets for therapy, are thereby activated by viruses to reduce type I IFN signaling.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Glycoproteins on the surface of the envelope serve to identify and bind to receptor sites on the host's membrane.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The particular set of viral proteins are engaged in a series of structural changes.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] When these changes are set/finished, there is then and only then, fusion with the host membrane.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] These glycoproteins mediate the interaction between virion and host cell, typically initiating the fusion between the viral envelope and the host's cellular membrane.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] In some cases, the virus with an envelope will form an endosome within the host cell.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] There are three main types of viral glycoproteins: Envelope proteins, membrane proteins, and spike proteins (E, M, and S).
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The viral envelope then fuses with the host's membrane, allowing the capsid and viral genome to enter and infect the host.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] All enveloped viruses also have a capsid, another protein layer, between the envelope and the genome.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The virus wraps its delicate nucleic acid with a protein shell known as the capsid, from the Latin capsa, meaning "box," in order to shield it from this hostile environment.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Similar to how numerous bricks come together to form a wall, the capsid is made up of one or more distinct protein types that repeatedly repeat to form the whole capsid.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] This repetitive pattern creates a robust but rather flexible capsid.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The nucleic acid inside the capsid is appropriately protected by its modest size and physical difficulty in opening it.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The nucleocapsid of the virion is made up of the nucleic acid and the capsid.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Remember that the genomes of most viruses are very small.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Genes code for instructions to make proteins, so small genomes cannot code for many proteins.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Therefore, the virion capsid consists of one or only a few proteins that repeat over and over to form the structure.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The viral nucleic acid would be physically too large to fit inside the capsid if it consisted of more than a few proteins.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The capsid, having a focused role of protecting the genome in addition to immune recognition evasion.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The viral capsid is known for its protection of RNA before it is inserted into the host cell, unlike the viral envelope which protects the protein capsid.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] The cell from which a virus buds often dies or is weakened, and sheds more viral particles for an extended period.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Viral envelope persistence, whether it be enveloped or naked, are a factor in determining longevity of a virus on inanimate surfaces.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Enveloped viruses possess great adaptability and can change in a short time in order to evade the immune system.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Enveloped viruses can cause persistent infections.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Vaccination against enveloped viruses can function by neutralizing the glycoprotein activity with antibodies.
[src:virology/viral-envelope] Eliminating the virus's ability to form an envelope—by removing or inactivating a structural protein—or to bud has been studied as a method for producing viruses incapable of replication.
[src:virology/viral-replication] The host cell must provide the energy and synthetic machinery and the low-molecular-weight precursors for the synthesis of viral proteins and nucleic acids.
[src:virology/viral-replication] It is the first step of viral replication.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Some viruses attach to the cell membrane of the host cell and inject its DNA or RNA into the host to initiate infection.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Attachment to a host cell is often achieved by a virus attachment protein that extends from the protein shell (capsid), of a virus.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This protein is responsible for binding to a surface receptor on the plasma membrane (or membrane carbohydrates) of a host cell.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Viruses can exploit normal cell receptor functions to allow attachment to occur by mimicking molecules that bind to host cell receptors.
[src:virology/viral-replication] For example, the rhinovirus uses their virus attachment protein to bind to the receptor ICAM-1on host cells that is normally used to facilitate adhesion between other host cells.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Entry, or penetration, is the second step in viral replication.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This step is characterized by the virus passing through the plasma membrane of the host cell.
[src:virology/viral-replication] The most common way a virus gains entry to the host cell is by receptor-mediated endocytosis, which comes at no energy cost to the virus, only the host cell.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Receptor-mediated endocytosis occurs when a molecule (in this case a virus) binds to receptor on the membrane of the cell.
[src:virology/viral-replication] A series of chemical signals from this binding causes the cell to wrap the attached virus in the plasma membrane around it forming a virus-containing vesicle inside the cell.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Viruses enter host cells using a variety of mechanisms, including the endocytic and non-endocytic routes.
[src:virology/viral-replication] They can also fuse at the plasma membrane and can spread within the host via fusion or cell-cell fusion.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Viruses attach to proteins on the host cell surface known as cellular receptors or attachment factors to aid entry.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Evidence shows that viruses utilize ion channels on the host cells during viral entry.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Fusion: External viral proteins promote the fusion of the virion with the plasma membrane.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This forms a pore in the host membrane, and after entry, the virion becomes uncoated, and its genomic material is then transferred into the cytoplasm.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Cell-to-cell fusion: Some viruses prompt specific protein expression on the surfaces of infected cells to attract uninfected cells.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This interaction causes the uninfected cell to fuse with the infected cell at lower pH levels to form a multinuclear cell known as a syncytium.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Endocytic routes: the process by which an intracellular vesicle is formed by membrane invagination, which results in the engulfment of extracellular and membrane-bound components, in this context, a virus.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Non-endocytic routes: the process by which viral particles are released into the cell by fusion of the extracellular viral envelope and the membrane of the host cell.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Uncoating is the third step in viral replication.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Uncoating is defined by the removal of the virion's protein "coat" and the release of its genetic material.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This step occurs in the same area that viral transcription occurs.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Different viruses have various mechanisms for uncoating.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Some RNA viruses such as Rhinoviruses use the low pH in a host cell's endosomes to activate their uncoating mechanism.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This involves the rhinovirus releasing a protein that creates holes in the endosome, and allows the virus to release its genome through the holes.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Many DNA viruses travel to the host cells nucleus and release their genetic material through nuclear pores.
[src:virology/viral-replication] The fourth step in the viral cycle is replication, which is defined by the rapid production of the viral genome.
[src:virology/viral-replication] How a virus undergoes replication relies on the type of genetic material the virus possesses.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Based on their genetic material, viruses will hijack the corresponding cellular machinery for said genetic material.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Viruses that contain double-stranded DNA (dsDNA) share the same kind of genetic material as all organisms, and can therefore use the replication enzymes in the host cell nucleus to replicate the viral genome.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Many RNA viruses typically replicate in the cytosol, and can directly access the host cell's ribosomes to manufacture viral proteins once the RNA is in a replicative form.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Viruses may undergo two types of life cycles: the lytic cycle and the lysogenic cycle.
[src:virology/viral-replication] In the lytic cycle, the virus introduces its genome into a host cell and initiates replication by hijacking the host's cellular machinery to make new copies of the virus.
[src:virology/viral-replication] In the lysogenic life cycle, the viral genome is incorporated into the host genome.
[src:virology/viral-replication] The host genome will undergo its normal life cycle, replicating and dividing replicating the viral genome along with its own.
[src:virology/viral-replication] The viral genome can be triggered to begin viral production via chemical and environmental stimulants.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Once a lysogenic virus enters the lytic life cycle, it will continue in the viral production pathways and proceed with transcription / mRNA production.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Assembly is when the newly manufactured viral proteins and genomes are gathered and put together to form immature viruses.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Like the other steps, how a particular virus is assembled is dependent on what type of virus it is.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Assembly can occur in the plasma membrane, cytosol, nucleus, golgi apparatus, and other locations within the host cell.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Some viruses only insert their genome into a capsid once the capsid is completed, while in other viruses the capsid will wrap around the genome as it is being copied.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This is the final step before a competent virus is formed.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This typically involves capsid modifications that are provided by enzymes (host or virus-encoded).
[src:virology/viral-replication] The final step in viral replication is release, which is when the newly assembled and mature viruses leave the host cell.
[src:virology/viral-replication] How a virus releases from the host cell is dependent on the type of virus it is.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This occurs when viruses that form their envelope from the host's plasma membrane bend the membrane around the capsid.
[src:virology/viral-replication] As the virus bends the plasma membrane it begins to wrap around the whole capsid until the virus is no longer attached to the host cell.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Another common way viruses leave the host cell is through cell lysis, where the viruses lyse the cell causing it to burst which releases mature viruses that were in the host cell.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Viruses are split into seven classes, according to the type of genetic material and method of mRNA production, each of which has its own families of viruses, which in turn have differing replication strategies themselves.
[src:virology/viral-replication] David Baltimore, a Nobel Prize-winning biologist, devised a system called the Baltimore Classification System to classify different viruses based on their unique replication strategy.
[src:virology/viral-replication] There are seven different replication strategies based on this system (Baltimore Class I, II, III, IV, V, VI, VII).
[src:virology/viral-replication] The seven classes of viruses are listed here briefly and in generalities.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This type of virus usually must enter the host nucleus before it is able to replicate.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Some of these viruses require host cell polymerases to replicate their genome, while others, such as adenoviruses or herpes viruses, encode their own replication factors.
[src:virology/viral-replication] However, in either case, replication of the viral genome is highly dependent on a cellular state permissive to DNA replication and, thus, on the cell cycle.
[src:virology/viral-replication] The virus may induce the cell to forcefully undergo cell division, which may lead to transformation of the cell and, ultimately, cancer.
[src:virology/viral-replication] An example of a family within this classification is the Adenoviridae.
[src:virology/viral-replication] There is only one well-studied example in which a class 1 family of viruses does not replicate within the nucleus.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This is the Poxvirus family, which comprises highly pathogenic viruses that infect vertebrates.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Viruses that fall under this category include ones that are not as well-studied, but still do pertain highly to vertebrates.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Two examples include the Circoviridae and Parvoviridae.
[src:virology/viral-replication] They replicate within the nucleus, and form a double-stranded DNA intermediate during replication.
[src:virology/viral-replication] A human Anellovirus called TTV is included within this classification and is found in almost all humans, infecting them asymptomatically in nearly every major organ.
[src:virology/viral-replication] RNA viruses: The polymerase of RNA viruses lacks the proofreading functions found in the polymerase of DNA viruses.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This contributed to RNA viruses having lower replicative fidelity compared to DNA viruses, causing RNA viruses to be highly mutagenic, which can increase their overall survival rate.
[src:virology/viral-replication] RNA viruses lack the capacity to identify and repair mismatched or damaged nucleotides, and thus, RNA genomes are prone to mutations introduced by mechanisms intrinsic and extrinsic to viral replication.
[src:virology/viral-replication] RNA viruses present a therapeutic double-edged sword: RNA viruses can withstand the challenge of antiviral drugs, cause epidemics, and infect multiple host species due to their mutagenic nature, making them difficult to treat.
[src:virology/viral-replication] However, the reverse transcriptase protein that often comes with the RNA virus can be used as an indirect target for RNA viruses, preventing transcription and synthesis of viral particles.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Like most viruses with RNA genomes, double-stranded RNA viruses do not rely on host polymerases for replication to the extent that viruses with DNA genomes do.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Double-stranded RNA viruses are not as well-studied as other classes.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This class includes two major families, the Reoviridae and Birnaviridae.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Replication is monocistronic and includes individual, segmented genomes, meaning that each of the genes codes for only one protein, unlike other viruses, which exhibit more complex translation.
[src:virology/viral-replication] These viruses consist of two types, however both share the fact that replication is primarily in the cytoplasm, and that replication is not as dependent on the cell cycle as that of DNA viruses.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This class of viruses is also one of the most-studied types of viruses, alongside the double-stranded DNA viruses.
[src:virology/viral-replication] The positive-sense RNA viruses and indeed all genes defined as **positive-sense** can be directly accessed by host ribosomes to immediately form proteins.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Examples of this class include the families Coronaviridae, Flaviviridae, and Picornaviridae.
[src:virology/viral-replication] The negative-sense RNA viruses and indeed all genes defined as **negative-sense** cannot be directly accessed by host ribosomes to immediately form proteins.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Instead, they must be transcribed by viral polymerases into the "readable" complementary positive-sense.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Examples in this class include the families Orthomyxoviridae, Paramyxoviridae, Bunyaviridae, Filoviridae, and Rhabdoviridae (which includes rabies).
[src:virology/viral-replication] A well-studied family of this class of viruses include the retroviruses.
[src:virology/viral-replication] One defining feature is the use of reverse transcriptase to convert the positive-sense RNA into DNA.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Instead of using the RNA for templates of proteins, they use DNA to create the templates, which is spliced into the host genome using integrase.
[src:virology/viral-replication] Replication can then commence with the help of the host cell's polymerases.
[src:virology/viral-replication] This small group of viruses, exemplified by the Hepatitis B virus, have a double-stranded, gapped genome that is subsequently filled in to form a covalently closed circle (cccDNA) that serves as a template for production of viral mRNAs and a subgenomic RNA.
[src:virology/viral-replication] The pregenome RNA serves as template for the viral reverse transcriptase and for production of the DNA genome.
[src:virology/virology] The identification of the causative agent of tobacco mosaic disease (TMV) as a novel pathogen by Martinus Beijerinck (1898) is now acknowledged as being the official beginning of the field of virology as a discipline distinct from bacteriology.
[src:virology/virology] He realized the source was neither a bacterial nor a fungal infection, but something completely different.
[src:virology/virology] Beijerinck used the word "virus" to describe the mysterious agent in his 'contagium vivum fluidum' ('contagious living fluid').
[src:virology/virology] Rosalind Franklin proposed the full structure of the tobacco mosaic virus in 1955.
[src:virology/virology] One main motivation for the study of viruses is because they cause many infectious diseases of plants and animals.
[src:virology/virology] The study of the manner in which viruses cause disease is viral pathogenesis.
[src:virology/virology] The degree to which a virus causes disease is its virulence.
[src:virology/virology] These fields of study are called plant virology, animal virology and human or medical virology.
[src:virology/virology] Virology began when there were no methods for propagating or visualizing viruses or specific laboratory tests for viral infections.
[src:virology/virology] The methods for separating viral nucleic acids (RNA and DNA) and proteins, which are now the mainstay of virology, did not exist.
[src:virology/virology] Now there are many methods for observing the structure and functions of viruses and their component parts.
[src:virology/virology] Thousands of different viruses are now known about and virologists often specialize in either the viruses that infect plants, or bacteria and other microorganisms, or animals.
[src:virology/virology] Viruses that infect humans are now studied by medical virologists.
[src:virology/virology] Virology is a broad subject covering biology, health, animal welfare, agriculture and ecology.
[src:virology/virology] Louis Pasteur was unable to find a causative agent for rabies and speculated about a pathogen too small to be detected by microscopes.
[src:virology/virology] In 1884, the French microbiologist Charles Chamberland invented the Chamberland filter (or Pasteur-Chamberland filter) with pores small enough to remove all bacteria from a solution passed through it.
[src:virology/virology] In 1892, the Russian biologist Dmitri Ivanovsky used this filter to study what is now known as the tobacco mosaic virus: crushed leaf extracts from infected tobacco plants remained infectious even after filtration to remove bacteria.
[src:virology/virology] Ivanovsky suggested the infection might be caused by a toxin produced by bacteria, but he did not pursue the idea.
[src:virology/virology] At the time it was thought that all infectious agents could be retained by filters and grown on a nutrient medium—this was part of the germ theory of disease.
[src:virology/virology] In 1898, the Dutch microbiologist Martinus Beijerinck repeated the experiments and became convinced that the filtered solution contained a new form of infectious agent.
[src:virology/virology] He observed that the agent multiplied only in cells that were dividing, but as his experiments did not show that it was made of particles, he called it a *contagium vivum fluidum* (soluble living germ) and reintroduced the word *virus*.
[src:virology/virology] Beijerinck maintained that viruses were liquid in nature, a theory later discredited by Wendell Stanley, who proved they were particulate.
[src:virology/virology] In the same year, Friedrich Loeffler and Paul Frosch passed the first animal virus, aphthovirus (the agent of foot-and-mouth disease), through a similar filter.
[src:virology/virology] In the early 20th century, the English bacteriologist Frederick Twort discovered a group of viruses that infect bacteria, now called bacteriophages (or commonly 'phages'), in 1915.
[src:virology/virology] The French-Canadian microbiologist Félix d'Herelle announced his independent discovery of bacteriophages in 1917.
[src:virology/virology] D'Herelle described viruses that, when added to bacteria on an agar plate, would produce areas of dead bacteria.
[src:virology/virology] He accurately diluted a suspension of these viruses and discovered that the highest dilutions (lowest virus concentrations), rather than killing all the bacteria, formed discrete areas of dead organisms.
[src:virology/virology] Counting these areas and multiplying by the dilution factor allowed him to calculate the number of viruses in the original suspension.
[src:virology/virology] Phages were heralded as a potential treatment for diseases such as typhoid and cholera, but their promise was forgotten with the development of penicillin.
[src:virology/virology] The development of bacterial resistance to antibiotics has renewed interest in the therapeutic use of bacteriophages.
[src:virology/virology] By the end of the 19th century, viruses were defined in terms of their infectivity, their ability to pass filters, and their requirement for living hosts.
[src:virology/virology] Viruses had been grown only in plants and animals.
[src:virology/virology] In 1906 Ross Granville Harrison invented a method for growing tissue in lymph, and in 1913 E.
[src:virology/virology] Lambert used this method to grow vaccinia virus in fragments of guinea pig corneal tissue.
[src:virology/virology] Maitland grew vaccinia virus in suspensions of minced hens' kidneys.
[src:virology/virology] Their method was not widely adopted until the 1950s when poliovirus was grown on a large scale for vaccine production.
[src:virology/virology] Another breakthrough came in 1931 when the American pathologist Ernest William Goodpasture and Alice Miles Woodruff grew influenza and several other viruses in fertilised chicken eggs.
[src:virology/virology] In 1949, John Franklin Enders, Thomas Weller, and Frederick Robbins grew poliovirus in cultured cells from aborted human embryonic tissue, the first virus to be grown without using solid animal tissue or eggs.
[src:virology/virology] This work enabled Hilary Koprowski, and then Jonas Salk, to make an effective polio vaccine.
[src:virology/virology] The first images of viruses were obtained upon the invention of electron microscopy in 1931 by the German engineers Ernst Ruska and Max Knoll.
[src:virology/virology] In 1935, American biochemist and virologist Wendell Meredith Stanley examined the tobacco mosaic virus and found it was mostly made of protein.
[src:virology/virology] A short time later, this virus was separated into protein and RNA parts.
[src:virology/virology] The tobacco mosaic virus was the first to be crystallised and its structure could, therefore, be elucidated in detail.
[src:virology/virology] The first X-ray diffraction pictures of the crystallised virus were obtained by Bernal and Fankuchen in 1941.
[src:virology/virology] Based on her X-ray crystallographic pictures, Rosalind Franklin discovered the full structure of the virus in 1955.
[src:virology/virology] The second half of the 20th century was the golden age of virus discovery, and most of the documented species of animal, plant, and bacterial viruses were discovered during these years.
[src:virology/virology] In 1946, bovine viral diarrhoea (a pestivirus) was first described.
[src:virology/virology] In 1957 equine arterivirus was discovered.
[src:virology/virology] In 1963 the hepatitis B virus was discovered by Baruch Blumberg.
[src:virology/virology] In 1965 Howard Temin described the first retrovirus.
[src:virology/virology] Reverse transcriptase, the enzyme that retroviruses use to make DNA copies of their RNA, was first described in 1970 by Temin and David Baltimore independently.
[src:virology/virology] In 1983 Luc Montagnier's team at the Pasteur Institute in France, first isolated the retrovirus now called HIV.
[src:virology/virology] In 1989 Michael Houghton's team at Chiron Corporation discovered hepatitis C.
[src:virology/virology] There are several approaches to detecting viruses; these include the detection of virus particles (virions) or their antigens or nucleic acids and infectivity assays.
[src:virology/virology] Viruses were seen for the first time in the 1930s when electron microscopes were invented.
[src:virology/virology] Unlike optical microscopes that observe with visible light, these microscopes use beams of electrons, which have a much shorter wavelength and can detect objects that cannot be seen using light microscopes.
[src:virology/virology] The highest magnification obtainable by electron microscopes is up to 10,000,000 times whereas for light microscopes it is around 1,500 times.
[src:virology/virology] Virologists often use negative staining to help visualise viruses.
[src:virology/virology] In this procedure, the viruses are suspended in a solution of metal salts such as uranium acetate.
[src:virology/virology] The atoms of metal are opaque to electrons and the viruses are seen as suspended in a dark background of metal atoms.
[src:virology/virology] This technique has been in use since the 1950s.
[src:virology/virology] Many viruses were discovered using this technique and negative staining electron microscopy is still a valuable weapon in a virologist's arsenal.
[src:virology/virology] Traditional electron microscopy has disadvantages in that viruses are damaged by drying in the high vacuum inside the electron microscope and the electron beam itself is destructive.
[src:virology/virology] In cryogenic electron microscopy the structure of viruses is preserved by embedding them in an environment of vitreous water.
[src:virology/virology] This allows the determination of biomolecular structures at near-atomic resolution, and has attracted wide attention to the approach as an alternative to X-ray crystallography or NMR spectroscopy for the determination of the structure of viruses.
[src:virology/virology] Viruses are obligate intracellular parasites, and because they only reproduce inside the living cells of a host, these cells are needed to grow them in the laboratory.
[src:virology/virology] For viruses that infect animals (usually called "animal viruses") cells grown in laboratory cell cultures are used.
[src:virology/virology] In the past, fertile hens' eggs were used and the viruses were grown on the membranes surrounding the embryo.
[src:virology/virology] This method is still used in the manufacture of some vaccines.
[src:virology/virology] For the viruses that infect bacteria, the bacteriophages, the bacteria growing in test tubes can be used directly.
[src:virology/virology] For plant viruses, the natural host plants can be used or, particularly when the infection is not obvious, so-called indicator plants, which show signs of infection more clearly.
[src:virology/virology] Viruses that have grown in cell cultures can be indirectly detected by the detrimental effect they have on the host cell.
[src:virology/virology] These cytopathic effects are often characteristic of the type of virus.
[src:virology/virology] For instance, herpes simplex viruses produce a characteristic "ballooning" of the cells, typically human fibroblasts.
[src:virology/virology] Some viruses, such as mumps virus cause red blood cells from chickens to firmly attach to the infected cells.
[src:virology/virology] This is called "haemadsorption" or "hemadsorption".
[src:virology/virology] Some viruses produce localised "lesions" in cell layers called plaques, which are useful in quantitation assays and in identifying the species of virus by plaque reduction assays.
[src:virology/virology] Viruses growing in cell cultures are used to measure their susceptibility to validated and novel antiviral drugs.
[src:virology/virology] Viruses are antigens that induce the production of antibodies.
[src:virology/virology] These antibodies can be used in laboratories to study viruses.
[src:virology/virology] Related viruses often react with each other's antibodies and some viruses can be named based on the antibodies they react with.
[src:virology/virology] The use of the antibodies, which were once exclusively derived from the serum (blood fluid) of animals, is called serology.
[src:virology/virology] Once an antibody–reaction has taken place in a test, other methods are needed to confirm this.
[src:virology/virology] Older methods included complement fixation tests, hemagglutination inhibition and virus neutralisation.
[src:virology/virology] Newer methods use enzyme immunoassays (EIA).
[src:virology/virology] In the years before PCR was invented immunofluorescence was used to quickly confirm viral infections.
[src:virology/virology] It is an infectivity assay that is virus species specific because antibodies are used.
[src:virology/virology] The antibodies are tagged with a dye that is luminescencent and when using an optical microscope with a modified light source, infected cells glow in the dark.
[src:virology/virology] PCR is a mainstay method for detecting viruses in all species including plants and animals.
[src:virology/virology] It works by detecting traces of virus specific RNA or DNA.
[src:virology/virology] It is very sensitive and specific, but can be easily compromised by contamination.
[src:virology/virology] Most of the tests used in veterinary virology and medical virology are based on PCR or similar methods such as transcription mediated amplification.
[src:virology/virology] When a novel virus emerges, such as the covid coronavirus, a specific test can be devised quickly so long as the viral genome has been sequenced and unique regions of the viral DNA or RNA identified.
[src:virology/virology] In laboratories, many of the diagnostic test for detecting viruses are nucleic acid amplification methods such as PCR.
[src:virology/virology] Some tests detect the viruses or their components as these include electron microscopy and enzyme-immunoassays.
[src:virology/virology] The so-called "home" or "self"-testing gadgets are usually lateral flow tests, which detect the virus using a tagged monoclonal antibody.
[src:virology/virology] These are also used in agriculture, food and environmental sciences.
[src:virology/virology] Counting viruses (quantitation) has always had an important role in virology and has become central to the control of some infections of humans where the viral load is measured.
[src:virology/virology] There are two basic methods: those that count the fully infective virus particles, which are called infectivity assays, and those that count all the particles including the defective ones.
[src:virology/virology] Infectivity assays measure the amount (concentration) of infective viruses in a sample of known volume.
[src:virology/virology] For host cells, plants or cultures of bacterial or animal cells are used.
[src:virology/virology] Laboratory animals such as mice have also been used particularly in veterinary virology.
[src:virology/virology] These are assays are either quantitative where the results are on a continuous scale or quantal, where an event either occurs or it does not.
[src:virology/virology] Quantitative assays give absolute values and quantal assays give a statistical probability such as the volume of the test sample needed to ensure 50% of the hosts cells, plants or animals are infected.
[src:virology/virology] This is called the median infectious dose or ID 50.
[src:virology/virology] Infective bacteriophages can be counted by seeding them onto "lawns" of bacteria in culture dishes.
[src:virology/virology] When at low concentrations, the viruses form holes in the lawn that can be counted.
[src:virology/virology] The number of viruses is then expressed as plaque forming units.
[src:virology/virology] For the bacteriophages that reproduce in bacteria that cannot be grown in cultures, viral load assays are used.
[src:virology/virology] The FFA is particularly useful for quantifying classes of viruses that do not lyse the cell membranes, as these viruses would not be amenable to the plaque assay.
[src:virology/virology] Plates are subsequently probed with fluorescently labeled antibodies against a viral antigen, and fluorescence microscopy is used to count and quantify the number of foci.
[src:virology/virology] The FFA method typically yields results in less time than plaque or fifty-percent-tissue-culture-infective-dose (TCID50) assays, but it can be more expensive in terms of required reagents and equipment.
[src:virology/virology] Assay completion time is also dependent on the size of area that the user is counting.
[src:virology/virology] A larger area will require more time but can provide a more accurate representation of the sample.
[src:virology/virology] Results of the FFA are expressed as focus forming units per milliliter, or FFU/mL.
[src:virology/virology] When an assay for measuring the infective virus particle is done (Plaque assay, Focus assay), viral titre often refers to the concentration of infectious viral particles, which is different from the total viral particles.
[src:virology/virology] Viral load assays usually count the number of viral genomes present rather than the number of particles and use methods similar to PCR.
[src:virology/virology] Viral load tests are an important in the control of infections by HIV.
[src:virology/virology] This versatile method can be used for plant viruses.
[src:virology/virology] Molecular virology is the study of viruses at the level of nucleic acids and proteins.
[src:virology/virology] The methods invented by molecular biologists have all proven useful in virology.
[src:virology/virology] Their small sizes and relatively simple structures make viruses an ideal candidate for study by these techniques.
[src:virology/virology] For further study, viruses grown in the laboratory need purifying to remove contaminants from the host cells.
[src:virology/virology] The methods used often have the advantage of concentrating the viruses, which makes it easier to investigate them.
[src:virology/virology] Centrifuges are often used to purify viruses.
[src:virology/virology] Low speed centrifuges, i.e. those with a top speed of 10,000 revolutions per minute (rpm) are not powerful enough to concentrate viruses, but ultracentrifuges with a top speed of around 100,000 rpm, are and this difference is used in a method called differential centrifugation.
[src:virology/virology] In this method the larger and heavier contaminants are removed from a virus mixture by low speed centrifugation.
[src:virology/virology] The viruses, which are small and light and are left in suspension, are then concentrated by high speed centrifugation.
[src:virology/virology] Following differential centrifugation, virus suspensions often remain contaminated with debris that has the same sedimentation coefficient and are not removed by the procedure.
[src:virology/virology] In these cases a modification of centrifugation, called buoyant density centrifugation, is used.
[src:virology/virology] In this method the viruses recovered from differential centrifugation are centrifuged again at very high speed for several hours in dense solutions of sugars or salts that form a density gradient, from low to high, in the tube during the centrifugation.
[src:virology/virology] In some cases, preformed gradients are used where solutions of steadily decreasing density are carefully overlaid on each other.
[src:virology/virology] Like an object in the Dead Sea, despite the centrifugal force the virus particles cannot sink into solutions that are more dense than they are and they form discrete layers of, often visible, concentrated viruses in the tube.
[src:virology/virology] Caesium chloride is often used for these solutions as it is relatively inert but easily self-forms a gradient when centrifuged at high speed in an ultracentrifuge.
[src:virology/virology] Buoyant density centrifugation can also be used to purify the components of viruses such as their nucleic acids or proteins.
[src:virology/virology] The separation of molecules based on their electric charge is called electrophoresis.
[src:virology/virology] Viruses and all their components can be separated and purified using this method.
[src:virology/virology] This is usually done in a supporting medium such as agarose and polyacrylamide gels.
[src:virology/virology] The separated molecules are revealed using stains such as coomasie blue, for proteins, or ethidium bromide for nucleic acids.
[src:virology/virology] In some instances the viral components are rendered radioactive before electrophoresis and are revealed using photographic film in a process known as autoradiography.
[src:virology/virology] As most viruses are too small to be seen by a light microscope, sequencing is one of the main tools in virology to identify and study the virus.
[src:virology/virology] Traditional Sanger sequencing and next-generation sequencing (NGS) are used to sequence viruses in basic and clinical research, as well as for the diagnosis of emerging viral infections, molecular epidemiology of viral pathogens, and drug-resistance testing.
[src:virology/virology] There are more than 2.3 million unique viral sequences in GenBank.
[src:virology/virology] NGS has surpassed traditional Sanger as the most popular approach for generating viral genomes.
[src:virology/virology] Viral genome sequencing as become a central method in viral epidemiology and viral classification.
[src:virology/virology] Data from the sequencing of viral genomes can be used to determine evolutionary relationships and this is called phylogenetic analysis.
[src:virology/virology] Software, such as PHYLIP, is used to draw phylogenetic trees.
[src:virology/virology] This analysis is also used in studying the spread of viral infections in communities (epidemiology).
[src:virology/virology] When purified viruses or viral components are needed for diagnostic tests or vaccines, cloning can be used instead of growing the viruses.
[src:virology/virology] At the start of the COVID-19 pandemic the availability of the severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 RNA sequence enabled tests to be manufactured quickly.
[src:virology/virology] There are several proven methods for cloning viruses and their components.
[src:virology/virology] Small pieces of DNA called cloning vectors are often used and the most common ones are laboratory modified plasmids (small circular molecules of DNA produced by bacteria).
[src:virology/virology] The viral nucleic acid, or a part of it, is inserted in the plasmid, which is the copied many times over by bacteria.
[src:virology/virology] This recombinant DNA can then be used to produce viral components without the need for native viruses.
[src:virology/virology] The viruses that reproduce in bacteria, archaea and fungi are informally called "phages", and the ones that infect bacteria – bacteriophages – in particular are useful in virology and biology in general.
[src:virology/virology] Bacteriophages were some of the first viruses to be discovered, early in the twentieth century, and because they are relatively easy to grow quickly in laboratories, much of our understanding of viruses originated by studying them.
[src:virology/virology] Bacteriophages, long known for their positive effects in the environment, are used in phage display techniques for screening proteins DNA sequences.
[src:virology/virology] They are a powerful tool in molecular biology.
[src:virology/virology] All viruses have genes which are studied using genetics.
[src:virology/virology] All the techniques used in molecular biology, such as cloning, creating mutations RNA silencing are used in viral genetics.
[src:virology/virology] Reassortment is the switching of genes from different parents and it is particularly useful when studying the genetics of viruses that have segmented genomes (fragmented into two or more nucleic acid molecules) such as influenza viruses and rotaviruses.
[src:virology/virology] The genes that encode properties such as serotype can be identified in this way.
[src:virology/virology] Often confused with reassortment, recombination is also the mixing of genes but the mechanism differs in that *stretches* of DNA or RNA molecules, as opposed to the full molecules, are joined during the RNA or DNA replication cycle.
[src:virology/virology] Recombination is not as common as reassortment in nature but it is a powerful tool in laboratories for studying the structure and functions of viral genes.
[src:virology/virology] Reverse genetics is a powerful research method in virology.
[src:virology/virology] In this procedure complementary DNA (cDNA) copies of virus genomes called "infectious clones" are used to produce genetically modified viruses that can be then tested for changes in say, virulence or transmissibility.
[src:virology/virology] A major branch of virology is virus classification.
[src:virology/virology] It is artificial in that it is not based on evolutionary phylogenetics but it is based on shared or distinguishing properties of viruses.
[src:virology/virology] It seeks to describe the diversity of viruses by naming and grouping them on the basis of similarities.
[src:virology/virology] In 1962, André Lwoff, Robert Horne, and Paul Tournier were the first to develop a means of virus classification, based on the Linnaean hierarchical system.
[src:virology/virology] This system based classification on phylum, class, order, family, genus, and species.
[src:virology/virology] Viruses were grouped according to their shared properties (not those of their hosts) and the type of nucleic acid forming their genomes.
[src:virology/virology] In 1966, the International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV) was formed.
[src:virology/virology] The system proposed by Lwoff, Horne and Tournier was initially not accepted by the ICTV because the small genome size of viruses and their high rate of mutation made it difficult to determine their ancestry beyond order.
[src:virology/virology] As such, the Baltimore classification system has come to be used to supplement the more traditional hierarchy.
[src:virology/virology] Starting in 2018, the ICTV began to acknowledge deeper evolutionary relationships between viruses that have been discovered over time and adopted a 15-rank classification system ranging from realm to species.
[src:virology/virology] Additionally, some species within the same genus are grouped into a *genogroup*.
[src:virology/virology] The ICTV developed the current classification system and wrote guidelines that put a greater weight on certain virus properties to maintain family uniformity.
[src:virology/virology] A unified taxonomy (a universal system for classifying viruses) has been established.
[src:virology/virology] Only a small part of the total diversity of viruses has been studied.
[src:virology/virology] As of 2021, 6 realms, 10 kingdoms, 17 phyla, 2 subphyla, 39 classes, 65 orders, 8 suborders, 233 families, 168 subfamilies, 2,606 genera, 84 subgenera, and 10,434 species of viruses have been defined by the ICTV.
[src:virology/virology] The general taxonomic structure of taxon ranges and the suffixes used in taxonomic names are shown hereafter.
[src:virology/virology] As of 2021, the ranks of subrealm, subkingdom, and subclass are unused, whereas all other ranks are in use.
[src:virology/virology] The Nobel Prize-winning biologist David Baltimore devised the Baltimore classification system.
[src:virology/virology] The Baltimore classification of viruses is based on the mechanism of mRNA production.
[src:virology/virology] Viruses must generate mRNAs from their genomes to produce proteins and replicate themselves, but different mechanisms are used to achieve this in each virus family.
[src:virology/virology] Viral genomes may be single-stranded (ss) or double-stranded (ds), RNA or DNA, and may or may not use reverse transcriptase (RT).
[src:virology/virology] In addition, ssRNA viruses may be either sense (+) or antisense (−).
[src:virology/virus-p01] A **virus** is a submicroscopic infectious agent that replicates only inside the living cells of an organism.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses infect all life forms, from animals and plants to microorganisms, including bacteria and archaea.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses are found in almost every ecosystem on Earth and are the most numerous type of biological entity.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Since Dmitri Ivanovsky's 1892 article describing a non-bacterial pathogen infecting tobacco plants and the discovery of the tobacco mosaic virus by Martinus Beijerinck in 1898, more than 16,000 of the millions of virus species have been described in detail.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The study of viruses is known as virology, a subspeciality of microbiology.
[src:virology/virus-p01] When infected, a host cell is often forced to rapidly produce thousands of copies of the original virus.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The shapes of these virus particles range from simple helical and icosahedral forms to more complex structures.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Most virus species have virions too small to be seen with an optical microscope and are one-hundredth the size of most bacteria.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The origins of viruses in the evolutionary history of life are still unclear.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Some viruses may have evolved from plasmids, which are pieces of DNA that can move between cells.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Other viruses may have evolved from bacteria.
[src:virology/virus-p01] In evolution, viruses are an important means of horizontal gene transfer, which increases genetic diversity in a way analogous to sexual reproduction.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses are considered by some biologists to be a life form, because they carry genetic material, reproduce, and evolve through natural selection, although they lack some key characteristics, such as cell structure, that are generally considered necessary criteria for defining life.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Because they possess some but not all such qualities, viruses have been described as "organisms at the edge of life" and as replicators.
[src:virology/virus-p01] One transmission pathway is through disease-bearing organisms known as vectors: for example, viruses are often transmitted from plant to plant by insects that feed on plant sap, such as aphids; and viruses in animals can be carried by blood-sucking insects.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Many viruses spread in the air by coughing and sneezing, including influenza viruses, SARS-CoV-2, chickenpox, smallpox, and measles.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Norovirus and rotavirus, common causes of viral gastroenteritis, are transmitted by the faecal–oral route, passed by hand-to-mouth contact or in food or water.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The infectious dose of norovirus required to produce infection in humans is fewer than 100 particles.
[src:virology/virus-p01] HIV is one of several viruses transmitted through sexual contact and by exposure to infected blood.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The variety of host cells that a virus can infect is called its host range: this is narrow for viruses specialized to infect only a few species, or broad for viruses capable of infecting many.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viral infections in animals provoke an immune response that usually eliminates the infecting virus.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Immune responses can also be produced by vaccines, which confer an artificially acquired immunity to the specific viral infection.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Some viruses, including those that cause HIV/AIDS, HPV infection, and viral hepatitis, evade these immune responses and result in chronic infections.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Several classes of antiviral drugs have been developed and around 100 individual antiviral drugs or combinations of them are used worldwide.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The English word "virus" comes from the Latin word *vīrus*, which refers to poison and other noxious liquids.
[src:virology/virus-p01] *Vīrus* comes from the same Indo-European root as Sanskrit वि॒ष (*viṣa*), and Ancient Greek ἰός (*iós*), which all mean 'poison'.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The first attested use of "virus" in English appeared in 1398 in John Trevisa's translation of Bartholomeus Anglicus's *De Proprietatibus Rerum*.
[src:virology/virus-p01] *Virulent*, from Latin *virulentus* ('poisonous'), dates to c.
[src:virology/virus-p01] A meaning of 'agent that causes infectious disease' is first recorded in 1728, long before the discovery of viruses by Dmitri Ivanovsky in 1892.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The English plural is *viruses* (sometimes also *vira*), whereas the Latin word is a mass noun, which has no classically attested plural (*vīra* is used in Neo-Latin).
[src:virology/virus-p01] The term *virion* (plural *virions*), which dates from 1959, is also used to refer to a single viral particle that is released from the cell and is capable of infecting other cells of the same type.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses are found wherever there is life and have probably existed since living cells first evolved.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The origin of viruses is unclear because they do not form fossils, so molecular techniques are used to infer how they arose.
[src:virology/virus-p01] In addition, viral genetic material occasionally integrates into the germline of the host organisms, by which they can be passed on vertically to the offspring of the host for many generations.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This provides an invaluable source of information for paleovirologists to trace back ancient viruses that existed as far back as millions of years ago.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Over time, genes not required by their parasitism were lost.
[src:virology/virus-p01] are living cells that, like viruses, can reproduce only inside host cells.
[src:virology/virus-p01] They lend support to this hypothesis, as their dependence on parasitism is likely to have caused the loss of genes that enabled them to survive outside a cell.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Some viruses may have evolved from bits of DNA or RNA that "escaped" from the genes of a larger organism.
[src:virology/virus-p01] (molecules of DNA that replicate and move around to different positions within the genes of the cell).
[src:virology/virus-p01] and could be the origin of some viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p01] at the same time that cells first appeared on Earth and would have been dependent on cellular life for billions of years.
[src:virology/virus-p01] are molecules of RNA that are not classified as viruses because they lack a protein coat.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viroids are significant pathogens of plants.
[src:virology/virus-p01] They do not code for proteins but interact with the host cell and use the host machinery for their replication.
[src:virology/virus-p01] similar to viroids but has a protein coat derived from hepatitis B virus and cannot produce one of its own.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Although hepatitis delta virus genome may replicate independently once inside a host cell, it requires the help of hepatitis B virus to provide a protein coat so that it can be transmitted to new cells.
[src:virology/virus-p01] " and may represent evolutionary intermediates of viroids and viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses are now recognised as ancient and as having origins that pre-date the divergence of life into the three domains.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This discovery has led modern virologists to reconsider and re-evaluate these three classical hypotheses.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The evidence for an ancestral world of RNA cells and computer analysis of viral and host DNA sequences give a better understanding of the evolutionary relationships between different viruses and may help identify the ancestors of modern viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p01] To date, such analyses have not proved which of these hypotheses is correct.
[src:virology/virus-p01] It seems unlikely that all currently known viruses have a common ancestor, and viruses have probably arisen numerous times in the past by one or more mechanisms.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The first evidence of the existence of viruses came from experiments with filters that had pores small enough to retain bacteria.
[src:virology/virus-p01] In 1892, Dmitri Ivanovsky used one of these filters to show that sap from a diseased tobacco plant remained infectious to healthy tobacco plants despite having been filtered.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Martinus Beijerinck called the filtered, infectious substance a "virus" and this discovery is considered to be the beginning of virology.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The subsequent discovery and partial characterization of bacteriophages by Frederick Twort and Félix d'Herelle further catalyzed the field, and by the early 20th century many viruses had been discovered.
[src:virology/virus-p01] In 1926, Thomas Milton Rivers defined viruses as obligate parasites.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses were demonstrated to be particles, rather than a fluid, by Wendell Meredith Stanley, and the invention of the electron microscope in 1931 allowed their complex structures to be visualised.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Scientific opinions differ on whether viruses are a form of life or organic structures that interact with living organisms.
[src:virology/virus-p01] They have been described as "organisms at the edge of life", since they resemble organisms in that they possess genes, evolve by natural selection, and reproduce by creating multiple copies of themselves through self-assembly.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Although they have genes, they do not have a cellular structure, which is often seen as the basic unit of life.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses do not have their own metabolism and require a host cell to make new products.
[src:virology/virus-p01] They therefore cannot naturally reproduce outside a host cell—although some bacteria such as rickettsia and chlamydia are considered living organisms despite the same limitation.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Accepted forms of life use cell division to reproduce, whereas viruses spontaneously assemble within cells.
[src:virology/virus-p01] They differ from autonomous growth of crystals as they inherit genetic mutations while being subject to natural selection.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Virus self-assembly within host cells has implications for the study of the origin of life, as it lends further credence to the hypothesis that life could have started as self-assembling organic molecules.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The virocell model first proposed by Patrick Forterre considers the infected cell to be the "living form" of viruses and that virus particles (virions) are analogous to spores.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Although the living versus non-living debate continues, the virocell model has gained some acceptance.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Virions of some of the most common human viruses with their relative size.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This spherical virus also has icosahedral symmetry.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses display a wide diversity of sizes and shapes, called 'morphologies'.
[src:virology/virus-p01] In general, viruses are much smaller than bacteria and more than a thousand bacteriophage viruses would fit inside an *Escherichia coli* bacterium's cell.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Many viruses that have been studied are spherical and have a diameter between 20 and 300 nanometres.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Some filoviruses, which are filaments, have a total length of up to 1400 nm; their diameters are only about 80 nm.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Most viruses cannot be seen with an optical microscope, so scanning and transmission electron microscopes are used to visualise them.
[src:virology/virus-p01] To increase the contrast between viruses and the background, electron-dense "stains" are used.
[src:virology/virus-p01] These are solutions of salts of heavy metals, such as tungsten, that scatter the electrons from regions covered with the stain.
[src:virology/virus-p01] When virions are coated with stain (positive staining), fine detail is obscured.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Negative staining overcomes this problem by staining the background only.
[src:virology/virus-p01] A complete virus particle, known as a *virion*, consists of nucleic acid surrounded by a protective coat of protein called a capsid.
[src:virology/virus-p01] These are formed from protein subunits called capsomeres.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses can have a lipid "envelope" derived from the host cell membrane.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The capsid is made from proteins encoded by the viral genome and its shape serves as the basis for morphological distinction.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Virally-coded protein subunits will self-assemble to form a capsid, in general requiring the presence of the virus genome.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Complex viruses code for proteins that assist in the construction of their capsid.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Proteins associated with nucleic acid are known as nucleoproteins, and the association of viral capsid proteins with viral nucleic acid is called a nucleocapsid.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The capsid and entire virus structure can be mechanically (physically) probed through atomic force microscopy.
[src:virology/virus-p01] structure, which may have a central cavity, or tube.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This arrangement results in virions which can be short and highly rigid rods, or long and very flexible filaments.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The genetic material (typically single-stranded RNA, but single-stranded DNA in some cases) is bound into the protein helix by interactions between the negatively charged nucleic acid and positive charges on the protein.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Overall, the length of a helical capsid is related to the length of the nucleic acid contained within it, and the diameter is dependent on the size and arrangement of capsomeres.
[src:virology/virus-p01] is the optimum way of forming a closed shell from identical subunits.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The minimum number of capsomeres required for each triangular face is 3, which gives 60 for the icosahedron.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Many viruses, such as rotavirus, have more than 60 capsomers and appear spherical but they retain this symmetry.
[src:virology/virus-p01] To achieve this, the capsomeres at the apices are surrounded by five other capsomeres and are called pentons.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Hexons are in essence flat and pentons, which form the 12 vertices, are curved.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The same protein may act as the subunit of both the pentamers and hexamers or they may be composed of different proteins.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This is an icosahedron elongated along the fivefold axis and is a common arrangement of the heads of bacteriophages.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This structure is composed of a cylinder with a cap at either end.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This membrane is studded with proteins coded for by the viral genome and host genome; the lipid membrane itself and any carbohydrates present originate entirely from the host.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Most enveloped viruses are dependent on the envelope for their infectivity.
[src:virology/virus-p01] These viruses possess a capsid that is neither purely helical nor purely icosahedral, and that may possess extra structures such as protein tails or a complex outer wall.
[src:virology/virus-p01] base plate with protruding protein tail fibres.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This tail structure acts like a molecular syringe, attaching to the bacterial host and then injecting the viral genome into the cell.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The poxviruses are large, complex viruses that have an unusual morphology.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The viral genome is associated with proteins within a central disc structure known as a nucleoid.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The nucleoid is surrounded by a membrane and two lateral bodies of unknown function.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The virus has an outer envelope with a thick layer of protein studded over its surface.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The whole virion is slightly pleomorphic, ranging from ovoid to brick-shaped.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Mimivirus is one of the largest characterised viruses, with a capsid diameter of 400 nm.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Protein filaments measuring 100 nm project from the surface.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The capsid appears hexagonal under an electron microscope, therefore the capsid is probably icosahedral.
[src:virology/virus-p01] In 2011, researchers discovered the largest then known virus in samples of water collected from the ocean floor off the coast of Las Cruces, Chile.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Provisionally named *Megavirus chilensis*, it can be seen with a basic optical microscope.
[src:virology/virus-p01] In 2013, the Pandoravirus genus was discovered in Chile and Australia, and has genomes about twice as large as Megavirus and Mimivirus.
[src:virology/virus-p01] All giant viruses have dsDNA genomes and they are classified into several families: *Mimiviridae, Pithoviridae, Pandoraviridae, Phycodnaviridae,* and the *Mollivirus* genus.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Some viruses that infect Archaea have complex structures unrelated to any other form of virus, with a wide variety of unusual shapes, ranging from spindle-shaped structures to viruses that resemble hooked rods, teardrops or even bottles.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Other archaeal viruses resemble the tailed bacteriophages, and can have multiple tail structures.
[src:virology/virus-p01] An enormous variety of genomic structures can be seen among viral species; as a group, they contain more structural genomic diversity than plants, animals, archaea, or bacteria.
[src:virology/virus-p01] There are millions of different types of viruses, and 16,215 species have been defined.
[src:virology/virus-p01] As of January 2021, the NCBI Virus genome database has more than 193,000 complete genome sequences, but there are doubtlessly many more to be discovered.
[src:virology/virus-p01] A virus has either a DNA or an RNA genome and is called a DNA virus or an RNA virus, respectively.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Some RNA viruses, for example retroviruses, have a stage in their replication cycle where the genome is encoded in DNA.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Plant viruses tend to have single-stranded RNA genomes and bacteriophages tend to have double-stranded DNA genomes.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viral genomes are circular, as in the polyomaviruses, or linear, as in the adenoviruses.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The type of nucleic acid is irrelevant to the shape of the genome.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Among RNA viruses and certain DNA viruses, the genome is often divided into separate parts, in which case it is called segmented.
[src:virology/virus-p01] For RNA viruses, each segment often codes for only one protein and they are usually found together in one capsid.
[src:virology/virus-p01] All segments are not required to be in the same virion for the virus to be infectious, as demonstrated by brome mosaic virus and several other plant viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p01] A viral genome, irrespective of nucleic acid type, is almost always either single-stranded (ss) or double-stranded (ds).
[src:virology/virus-p01] Single-stranded genomes consist of an unpaired nucleic acid, analogous to one-half of a ladder split down the middle.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Double-stranded genomes consist of two complementary paired nucleic acids, analogous to a ladder.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The virus particles of some virus families, such as those belonging to the *Hepadnaviridae*, contain a genome that is partially double-stranded and partially single-stranded.
[src:virology/virus-p01] For most viruses with RNA genomes and some with single-stranded DNA (ssDNA) genomes, the single strands are said to be either positive-sense (called the 'plus-strand') or negative-sense (called the 'minus-strand'), depending on if they are complementary to the viral messenger RNA (mRNA).
[src:virology/virus-p01] Positive-sense viral RNA is in the same sense as viral mRNA and thus at least a part of it can be immediately translated by the host cell.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Negative-sense viral RNA is complementary to mRNA and thus must be converted to positive-sense RNA by an RNA-dependent RNA polymerase before translation.
[src:virology/virus-p01] DNA nomenclature for viruses with genomic ssDNA is similar to RNA nomenclature, in that positive-strand viral ssDNA is identical in sequence to the viral mRNA and is thus a coding strand, while negative-sense viral ssDNA is complementary to the viral mRNA and is thus a template strand.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Several types of ssDNA and ssRNA viruses have genomes that are ambisense in that transcription can occur off both strands in a double-stranded replicative intermediate.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Examples include geminiviruses, which are ssDNA plant viruses and arenaviruses, which are ssRNA viruses of animals.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Genome size varies greatly between species.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The smallest—the ssDNA circoviruses, family *Circoviridae*—code for only two proteins and have a genome size of only two kilobases; the largest—the pandoraviruses—have genome sizes of around two megabases which code for about 2500 proteins.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Virus genes rarely have introns and often are arranged in the genome so that they overlap.
[src:virology/virus-p01] In general, RNA viruses have smaller genome sizes than DNA viruses because of a higher error-rate when replicating, and have a maximum upper size limit.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Beyond this, errors when replicating render the virus useless or uncompetitive.
[src:virology/virus-p01] To compensate, RNA viruses often have segmented genomes—the genome is split into smaller molecules—thus reducing the chance that an error in a single-component genome will incapacitate the entire genome.
[src:virology/virus-p01] In contrast, DNA viruses generally have larger genomes because of the high fidelity of their replication enzymes.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Single-strand DNA viruses are an exception to this rule, as mutation rates for these genomes can approach the extreme of the ssRNA virus case.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses undergo genetic change by several mechanisms.
[src:virology/virus-p01] These include a process called antigenic drift where individual bases in the DNA or RNA mutate to other bases.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Most of these point mutations are "silent"—they do not change the protein that the gene encodes—but others can confer evolutionary advantages such as resistance to antiviral drugs.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Antigenic shift occurs when there is a major change in the genome of the virus.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This can be a result of recombination or reassortment.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The Influenza A virus is highly prone to reassortment; occasionally this has resulted in novel strains which have caused pandemics.
[src:virology/virus-p01] RNA viruses often exist as quasispecies or swarms of viruses of the same species but with slightly different genome nucleoside sequences.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Such quasispecies are a prime target for natural selection.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Segmented genomes confer evolutionary advantages; different strains of a virus with a segmented genome can shuffle and combine genes and produce progeny viruses (or offspring) that have unique characteristics.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This is called reassortment or 'viral sex'.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Genetic recombination is a process by which a strand of DNA (or RNA) is broken and then joined to the end of a different DNA (or RNA) molecule.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This can occur when viruses infect cells simultaneously and studies of viral evolution have shown that recombination has been rampant in the species studied.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Recombination is common to both RNA and DNA viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Coronaviruses have a single-strand positive-sense RNA genome.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Replication of the genome is catalyzed by an RNA-dependent RNA polymerase.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The mechanism of recombination used by coronaviruses likely involves template switching by the polymerase during genome replication.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This process appears to be an adaptation for coping with genome damage.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viral populations do not grow through cell division, because they are acellular.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Instead, they use the machinery and metabolism of a host cell to produce multiple copies of themselves, and they assemble in the cell.
[src:virology/virus-p01] When infected, the host cell is forced to rapidly produce thousands of copies of the original virus.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The genetic material within virus particles, and the method by which the material is replicated, varies considerably between different types of viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p01] If the cell has the appropriate receptor on its surface, these viruses enter the cell either by direct fusion with the cell membrane (e.g., herpesviruses) or—more usually—by receptor-mediated endocytosis.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Most DNA viruses are entirely dependent on the host cell's DNA and RNA synthesising machinery and RNA processing machinery.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses with larger genomes may encode much of this machinery themselves.
[src:virology/virus-p01] In eukaryotes, the viral genome must cross the cell's nuclear membrane to access this machinery, while in bacteria it need only enter the cell.
[src:virology/virus-p01] RNA viruses can be placed into four different groups depending on their modes of replication.
[src:virology/virus-p01] (whether or not it can be used directly by ribosomes to make proteins) of single-stranded RNA viruses largely determines the replicative mechanism; the other major criterion is whether the genetic material is single-stranded or double-stranded.
[src:virology/virus-p01] enzymes to create copies of their genomes.
[src:virology/virus-p01] ) use an RNA intermediate during genome replication.
[src:virology/virus-p01] , or RNA-dependent DNA polymerase enzyme, to carry out the nucleic acid conversion.
[src:virology/virus-p01] pararetroviruses can give rise to infectious virus.
[src:virology/virus-p01] that inhibit the reverse transcriptase enzyme, e.g.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The range of structural and biochemical effects that viruses have on the host cell is extensive.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Most virus infections eventually result in the death of the host cell.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The causes of death include cell lysis, alterations to the cell's surface membrane and apoptosis.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Often cell death is caused by cessation of its normal activities because of suppression by virus-specific proteins, not all of which are components of the virus particle.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The distinction between cytopathic and harmless is gradual.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Some viruses, such as Epstein–Barr virus, can cause cells to proliferate without causing malignancy, while others, such as papillomaviruses, are established causes of cancer.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Some viruses cause no apparent changes to the infected cell.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Cells in which the virus is latent and inactive show few signs of infection and often function normally.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This causes persistent infections and the virus is often dormant for many months or years.
[src:virology/virus-p01] This is often the case with herpes viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Viruses are by far the most abundant biological entities on Earth and they outnumber all the others put together.
[src:virology/virus-p01] They infect all types of cellular life including animals, plants, bacteria and fungi.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Different types of viruses can infect only a limited range of hosts and many are species-specific.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Some, such as smallpox virus for example, can infect only one species—in this case humans, and are said to have a narrow host range.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Other viruses, such as rabies virus, can infect different species of mammals and are said to have a broad range.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The viruses that infect plants are harmless to animals, and most viruses that infect other animals are harmless to humans.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The host range of some bacteriophages is limited to a single strain of bacteria and they can be used to trace the source of outbreaks of infections by a method called phage typing.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The complete set of viruses in an organism or habitat is called the virome; for example, all human viruses constitute the human virome.
[src:virology/virus-p01] A **novel virus** is one that has not previously been recorded.
[src:virology/virus-p01] It can be a virus that is isolated from its natural reservoir or isolated as the result of spread to an animal or human host where the virus had not been identified before.
[src:virology/virus-p01] It can be an emergent virus, one that represents a new virus, but it can also be an extant virus that has not been previously identified.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The SARS-CoV-2 coronavirus that caused the COVID-19 pandemic is an example of a novel virus.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Classification seeks to describe the diversity of viruses by naming and grouping them on the basis of similarities.
[src:virology/virus-p01] Additionally, some species within the same genus are grouped into a **genogroup**.
[src:virology/virus-p01] As of 2024, 7 realms, 11 kingdoms, 22 phyla, 4 subphyla, 49 classes, 93 orders, 12 suborders, 368 families, 213 subfamilies, 3,769 genera, 86 subgenera, and 16,215 species of viruses have been defined by the ICTV.
[src:virology/virus-p01] As of 2022, the ranks of subrealm, subkingdom, and subclass are unused, whereas all other ranks are in use.
[src:virology/virus-p01] The ICTV classification system is used in conjunction with the Baltimore classification system in modern virus classification.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Examples of common human diseases caused by viruses include the common cold, influenza, chickenpox, and cold sores.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Many serious diseases such as rabies, Ebola virus disease, AIDS (HIV), avian influenza, and SARS are caused by viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The relative ability of viruses to cause disease is described in terms of virulence.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Other diseases are under investigation to discover if they have a virus as the causative agent, such as the possible connection between human herpesvirus 6 (HHV6) and neurological diseases such as multiple sclerosis and chronic fatigue syndrome.
[src:virology/virus-p02] There is controversy over whether the bornavirus, previously thought to cause neurological diseases in horses, could be responsible for psychiatric illnesses in humans.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses have different mechanisms by which they produce disease in an organism, which depends largely on the viral species.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Mechanisms at the cellular level primarily include cell lysis, the breaking open and subsequent death of the cell.
[src:virology/virus-p02] In multicellular organisms, if enough cells die, the whole organism will start to suffer the effects.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Although viruses cause disruption of healthy homeostasis, resulting in disease, they may exist relatively harmlessly within an organism.
[src:virology/virus-p02] An example would include the ability of the herpes simplex virus, which causes cold sores, to remain in a dormant state within the human body.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This is called latency and is a characteristic of the herpes viruses, including Epstein–Barr virus, which causes glandular fever, and varicella zoster virus, which causes chickenpox and shingles.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Most people have been infected with at least one of these types of herpes virus.
[src:virology/virus-p02] These latent viruses might sometimes be beneficial, as the presence of the virus can increase immunity against bacterial pathogens, such as *Yersinia pestis*.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Some viruses can cause lifelong or chronic infections, where the viruses continue to replicate in the body despite the host's defence mechanisms.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This is common in hepatitis B virus and hepatitis C virus infections.
[src:virology/virus-p02] People chronically infected are known as carriers, as they serve as reservoirs of infectious virus.
[src:virology/virus-p02] In populations with a high proportion of carriers, the disease is said to be endemic.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viral epidemiology is the branch of medical science that deals with the transmission and control of virus infections in humans.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Transmission of viruses can be vertical, which means from mother to child, or horizontal, which means from person to person.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Examples of vertical transmission include hepatitis B virus and HIV, where the baby is born already infected with the virus.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Another, more rare, example is the varicella zoster virus, which, although causing relatively mild infections in children and adults, can be fatal to the foetus and newborn baby.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Horizontal transmission is the most common mechanism of spread of viruses in populations.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Horizontal transmission can occur when body fluids are exchanged during sexual activity, by exchange of saliva or when contaminated food or water is ingested.
[src:virology/virus-p02] It can also occur when aerosols containing viruses are inhaled or by insect vectors such as when infected mosquitoes penetrate the skin of a host.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Most types of viruses are restricted to just one or two of these mechanisms and they are referred to as "respiratory viruses" or "enteric viruses" and so forth.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The rate or speed of transmission of viral infections depends on factors that include population density, the number of susceptible individuals (i.e., those not immune), the quality of healthcare and the weather.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Epidemiology is used to break the chain of infection in populations during outbreaks of viral diseases.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Control measures are used that are based on knowledge of how the virus is transmitted.
[src:virology/virus-p02] It is important to find the source, or sources, of the outbreak and to identify the virus.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Once the virus has been identified, the chain of transmission can sometimes be broken by vaccines.
[src:virology/virus-p02] When vaccines are not available, sanitation and disinfection can be effective.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Often, infected people are isolated from the rest of the community, and those that have been exposed to the virus are placed in quarantine.
[src:virology/virus-p02] To control the outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease in cattle in Britain in 2001, thousands of cattle were slaughtered.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Most viral infections of humans and other animals have incubation periods during which the infection causes no signs or symptoms.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Incubation periods for viral diseases range from a few days to weeks, but are known for most infections.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Somewhat overlapping, but mainly following the incubation period, there is a period of communicability—a time when an infected individual or animal is contagious and can infect another person or animal.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This, too, is known for many viral infections, and knowledge of the length of both periods is important in the control of outbreaks.
[src:virology/virus-p02] When outbreaks cause an unusually high proportion of cases in a population, community, or region, they are called epidemics.
[src:virology/virus-p02] If outbreaks spread worldwide, they are called pandemics.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The 1918 flu pandemic, which lasted until 1919, was a category 5 influenza pandemic caused by an unusually severe and deadly influenza A virus.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The victims were often healthy young adults, in contrast to most influenza outbreaks, which predominantly affect juvenile, elderly, or otherwise-weakened patients.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Older estimates say it killed 40–50 million people, while more recent research suggests that it may have killed as many as 100 million people, or 5% of the world's population in 1918.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Although viral pandemics are rare events, HIV—which evolved from viruses found in monkeys and chimpanzees—has been pandemic since at least the 1980s.
[src:virology/virus-p02] During the 20th century there were four pandemics caused by influenza virus and those that occurred in 1918, 1957 and 1968 were severe.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Most researchers believe that HIV originated in sub-Saharan Africa during the 20th century; it is now a pandemic, with an estimated 37.9 million people now living with the disease worldwide.
[src:virology/virus-p02] There were about 770,000 deaths from AIDS in 2018.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) and the World Health Organization (WHO) estimate that AIDS has killed more than 25 million people since it was first recognised on 5 June 1981, making it one of the most destructive epidemics in recorded history.
[src:virology/virus-p02] In 2007 there were 2.7 million new HIV infections and 2 million HIV-related deaths.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Several highly lethal viral pathogens are members of the *Filoviridae*.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Filoviruses are filament-like viruses that cause viral hemorrhagic fever, and include ebolaviruses and marburgviruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Marburg virus, first discovered in 1967, attracted widespread press attention in April 2005 for an outbreak in Angola.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Ebola virus disease has also caused intermittent outbreaks with high mortality rates since 1976 when it was first identified.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The worst and most recent one is the 2013–2016 West Africa epidemic.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Except for smallpox, most pandemics are caused by newly evolved viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] These "emergent" viruses are usually mutants of less harmful viruses that have circulated previously either in humans or other animals.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) and Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) are caused by new types of coronaviruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Other coronaviruses are known to cause mild infections in humans, so the virulence and rapid spread of SARS infections—that by July 2003 had caused around 8,000 cases and 800 deaths—was unexpected and most countries were not prepared.
[src:virology/virus-p02] A related coronavirus, severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2), thought to have originated in bats, emerged in Wuhan, China in November 2019 and spread rapidly around the world.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Infections with the virus caused the COVID-19 pandemic that started in 2020.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Unprecedented restrictions in peacetime were placed on international travel, and curfews were imposed in several major cities worldwide in response to the pandemic.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses are an established cause of cancer in humans and other species.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viral cancers occur only in a minority of infected persons (or animals).
[src:virology/virus-p02] Cancer viruses come from a range of virus families, including both RNA and DNA viruses, and so there is no single type of "oncovirus" (an obsolete term originally used for acutely transforming retroviruses).
[src:virology/virus-p02] The development of cancer is determined by a variety of factors such as host immunity and mutations in the host.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses accepted to cause human cancers include some genotypes of human papillomavirus, hepatitis B virus, hepatitis C virus, Epstein–Barr virus, Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus and human T-lymphotropic virus.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The most recently discovered human cancer virus is a polyomavirus (Merkel cell polyomavirus) that causes most cases of a rare form of skin cancer called Merkel cell carcinoma.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Hepatitis viruses can develop into a chronic viral infection that leads to liver cancer.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Infection by human T-lymphotropic virus can lead to tropical spastic paraparesis and adult T-cell leukaemia.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Human papillomaviruses are an established cause of cancers of cervix, skin, anus, and penis.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Within the *Herpesviridae*, Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus causes Kaposi's sarcoma and body-cavity lymphoma, and Epstein–Barr virus causes Burkitt's lymphoma, Hodgkin's lymphoma, B lymphoproliferative disorder, and nasopharyngeal carcinoma.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Merkel cell polyomavirus closely related to SV40 and mouse polyomaviruses that have been used as animal models for cancer viruses for over 50 years.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The body's first line of defence against viruses is the innate immune system.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This comprises cells and other mechanisms that defend the host from infection in a non-specific manner.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This means that the cells of the innate system recognise, and respond to, pathogens in a generic way, but, unlike the adaptive immune system, it does not confer long-lasting or protective immunity to the host.
[src:virology/virus-p02] RNA interference is an important innate defence against viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Many viruses have a replication strategy that involves double-stranded RNA (dsRNA).
[src:virology/virus-p02] When such a virus infects a cell, it releases its RNA molecule or molecules, which immediately bind to a protein complex called a dicer that cuts the RNA into smaller pieces.
[src:virology/virus-p02] A biochemical pathway—the RISC complex—is activated, which ensures cell survival by degrading the viral mRNA.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Rotaviruses have evolved to avoid this defence mechanism by not uncoating fully inside the cell, and releasing newly produced mRNA through pores in the particle's inner capsid.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Their genomic dsRNA remains protected inside the core of the virion.
[src:virology/virus-p02] When the adaptive immune system of a vertebrate encounters a virus, it produces specific antibodies that bind to the virus and often render it non-infectious.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The first, called IgM, is highly effective at neutralising viruses but is produced by the cells of the immune system only for a few weeks.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The second, called IgG, is produced indefinitely.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The presence of IgM in the blood of the host is used to test for acute infection, whereas IgG indicates an infection sometime in the past.
[src:virology/virus-p02] IgG antibody is measured when tests for immunity are carried out.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Antibodies can continue to be an effective defence mechanism even after viruses have managed to gain entry to the host cell.
[src:virology/virus-p02] A protein that is in cells, called TRIM21, can attach to the antibodies on the surface of the virus particle.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This primes the subsequent destruction of the virus by the enzymes of the cell's proteasome system.
[src:virology/virus-p02] A second defence of vertebrates against viruses is called cell-mediated immunity and involves immune cells known as T cells.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The body's cells constantly display short fragments of their proteins on the cell's surface, and, if a T cell recognises a suspicious viral fragment there, the host cell is destroyed by 'killer T' cells and the virus-specific T-cells proliferate.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Cells such as the macrophage are specialists at this antigen presentation.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The production of interferon is an important host defence mechanism.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This is a hormone produced by the body when viruses are present.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Its role in immunity is complex; it eventually stops the viruses from reproducing by killing the infected cell and its close neighbours.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Not all virus infections produce a protective immune response in this way.
[src:virology/virus-p02] HIV evades the immune system by constantly changing the amino acid sequence of the proteins on the surface of the virion.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This is known as "escape mutation" as the viral epitopes escape recognition by the host immune response.
[src:virology/virus-p02] These persistent viruses evade immune control by sequestration, blockade of antigen presentation, cytokine resistance, evasion of natural killer cell activities, escape from apoptosis, and antigenic shift.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Other viruses, called 'neurotropic viruses', are disseminated by neural spread where the immune system may be unable to reach them due to immune privilege.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Because viruses use vital metabolic pathways within host cells to replicate, they are difficult to eliminate without using drugs that cause toxic effects to host cells in general.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The most effective medical approaches to viral diseases are vaccinations to provide immunity to infection, and antiviral drugs that selectively interfere with viral replication.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Vaccination is a cheap and effective way of preventing infections by viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Vaccines were used to prevent viral infections long before the discovery of the actual viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Their use has resulted in a dramatic decline in morbidity (illness) and mortality (death) associated with viral infections such as polio, measles, mumps and rubella.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Smallpox infections have been eradicated.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Vaccines are available to prevent over thirteen viral infections of humans, and more are used to prevent viral infections of animals.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Vaccines can consist of live-attenuated or killed viruses, viral proteins (antigens), or RNA.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Live vaccines contain weakened forms of the virus, which do not cause the disease but, nonetheless, confer immunity.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Live vaccines can be dangerous when given to people with a weak immunity (who are described as immunocompromised), because in these people, the weakened virus can cause the original disease.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Biotechnology and genetic engineering techniques are used to produce subunit vaccines.
[src:virology/virus-p02] These vaccines use only the capsid proteins of the virus.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Hepatitis B vaccine is an example of this type of vaccine.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Subunit vaccines are safe for immunocompromised patients because they cannot cause the disease.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The yellow fever virus vaccine, a live-attenuated strain called 17D, is probably the safest and most effective vaccine ever generated.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Antiviral drugs are often nucleoside analogues (fake DNA building-blocks), which viruses mistakenly incorporate into their genomes during replication.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The life-cycle of the virus is then halted because the newly synthesised DNA is inactive.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This is because these analogues lack the hydroxyl groups, which, along with phosphorus atoms, link together to form the strong "backbone" of the DNA molecule.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Examples of nucleoside analogues are aciclovir for Herpes simplex virus infections and lamivudine for HIV and hepatitis B virus infections.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Aciclovir is one of the oldest and most frequently prescribed antiviral drugs.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Other antiviral drugs in use target different stages of the viral life cycle.
[src:virology/virus-p02] HIV is dependent on a proteolytic enzyme called the HIV-1 protease for it to become fully infectious.
[src:virology/virus-p02] There is a large class of drugs called protease inhibitors that inactivate this enzyme.
[src:virology/virus-p02] There are around thirteen classes of antiviral drugs each targeting different viruses or stages of viral replication.
[src:virology/virus-p02] In 80% of people infected, the disease is chronic, and without treatment, they are infected for the remainder of their lives.
[src:virology/virus-p02] There are effective treatments that use direct-acting antivirals.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The treatment of chronic carriers of the hepatitis B virus has also been developed by using similar strategies that include lamivudine and other anti-viral drugs.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Around 100 individual antiviral drugs, or combinations of them, can be used to treat infections.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses infect all cellular life and, although viruses occur universally, each cellular species has its own specific range that often infects only that species.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Some viruses, called satellites, can replicate only within cells that have already been infected by another virus.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses are important pathogens of livestock.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Diseases such as foot-and-mouth disease and bluetongue are caused by viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Companion animals such as cats, dogs, and horses, if not vaccinated, are susceptible to serious viral infections.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Canine parvovirus is caused by a small DNA virus and infections are often fatal in pups.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Like all invertebrates, the honey bee is susceptible to many viral infections.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Most viruses co-exist harmlessly in their host and cause no signs or symptoms of disease.
[src:virology/virus-p02] There are many types of plant viruses, but often they cause only a loss of yield, and it is not economically viable to try to control them.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Plant viruses are often spread from plant to plant by organisms, known as vectors.
[src:virology/virus-p02] These are usually insects, but some fungi, nematode worms, single-celled organisms, and parasitic plants are vectors.
[src:virology/virus-p02] When control of plant virus infections is considered economical, for perennial fruits, for example, efforts are concentrated on killing the vectors and removing alternate hosts such as weeds.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Plant viruses cannot infect humans and other animals because they can reproduce only in living plant cells.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Originally from Peru, the potato has become a staple crop worldwide.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The potato virus Y causes disease in potatoes and related species including tomatoes and peppers.
[src:virology/virus-p02] In the 1980s, this virus acquired economical importance when it proved difficult to control in seed potato crops.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Transmitted by aphids, this virus can reduce crop yields by up to 80 per cent, causing significant losses to potato yields.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Plants have elaborate and effective defence mechanisms against viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] One of the most effective is the presence of so-called resistance (R) genes.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Each R gene confers resistance to a particular virus by triggering localised areas of cell death around the infected cell, which can often be seen with the unaided eye as large spots.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This stops the infection from spreading.
[src:virology/virus-p02] RNA interference is also an effective defence in plants.
[src:virology/virus-p02] When they are infected, plants often produce natural disinfectants that kill viruses, such as salicylic acid, nitric oxide, and reactive oxygen molecules.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Plant virus particles or virus-like particles (VLPs) have applications in both biotechnology and nanotechnology.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The capsids of most plant viruses are simple and robust structures and can be produced in large quantities either by the infection of plants or by expression in a variety of heterologous systems.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Plant virus particles can be modified genetically and chemically to encapsulate foreign material and can be incorporated into supramolecular structures for use in biotechnology.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Bacteriophages are a common and diverse group of viruses and are the most abundant biological entity in aquatic environments—there are up to ten times more of these viruses in the oceans than there are bacteria, reaching levels of 250,000,000 bacteriophages per millilitre of seawater.
[src:virology/virus-p02] These viruses infect specific bacteria by binding to surface receptor molecules and then entering the cell.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Within a short amount of time, in some cases, just minutes, bacterial polymerase starts translating viral mRNA into protein.
[src:virology/virus-p02] These proteins go on to become either new virions within the cell, helper proteins, which help assembly of new virions, or proteins involved in cell lysis.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viral enzymes aid in the breakdown of the cell membrane, and, in the case of the T4 phage, in just over twenty minutes after injection over three hundred phages could be released.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The major way bacteria defend themselves from bacteriophages is by producing enzymes that destroy foreign DNA.
[src:virology/virus-p02] These enzymes, called restriction endonucleases, cut up the viral DNA that bacteriophages inject into bacterial cells.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Bacteria also contain a system that uses CRISPR sequences to retain fragments of the genomes of viruses that the bacteria have come into contact with previously, which allows them to block the virus's replication through a form of RNA interference.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This genetic system provides bacteria with acquired immunity to infection.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Some bacteriophages are called "temperate" because they cause latent infections and do not immediately destroy their host cells.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Instead, their DNA is incorporated with the host cell's as a prophage.
[src:virology/virus-p02] These latent infections become productive when the prophage DNA is activated by stimuli such as changes in the environment.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The intestines of animals, including humans, contain temperate bacteriophages, which are activated by various stimuli including changes in diet and antibiotics.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Although first observed in bacteriophages, many other viruses are known to form proviruses including HIV.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Some viruses replicate within archaea: these are DNA viruses with unusual and sometimes unique shapes.
[src:virology/virus-p02] These viruses have been studied in most detail in the thermophilic archaea, particularly the orders Sulfolobales and Thermoproteales.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Defences against these viruses involve RNA interference from repetitive DNA sequences within archaean genomes that are related to the genes of the viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Most archaea have CRISPR–Cas systems as an adaptive defence against viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] These enable archaea to retain sections of viral DNA, which are then used to target and eliminate subsequent infections by the virus using a process similar to RNA interference.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses are the most abundant biological entity in aquatic environments.
[src:virology/virus-p02] There are about ten million of them in a teaspoon of seawater.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Most of these viruses are bacteriophages infecting heterotrophic bacteria and cyanophages infecting cyanobacteria and they are essential to the regulation of saltwater and freshwater ecosystems.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Bacteriophages are harmless to plants and animals but they are important mortality agents of phytoplankton, the base of the foodchain in aquatic environments.
[src:virology/virus-p02] They infect and destroy bacteria in aquatic microbial communities, and are one of the most important mechanisms of recycling carbon and nutrient cycling in marine environments.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The organic molecules released from the dead bacterial cells stimulate fresh bacterial and algal growth, in a process known as the viral shunt.
[src:virology/virus-p02] In particular, lysis of bacteria by viruses has been shown to enhance nitrogen cycling and stimulate phytoplankton growth.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viral activity may also affect the biological pump, the process whereby carbon is sequestered in the deep ocean.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Microorganisms constitute more than 90% of the biomass in the sea.
[src:virology/virus-p02] It is estimated that viruses kill approximately 20% of this biomass each day and that there are 10 to 15 times as many viruses in the oceans as there are bacteria and archaea.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses are also major agents responsible for the destruction of phytoplankton including harmful algal blooms.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The number of viruses in the oceans decreases further offshore and deeper into the water, where there are fewer host organisms.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Like any organism, marine mammals are susceptible to viral infections.
[src:virology/virus-p02] In 1988 and 2002, thousands of harbour seals were killed in Europe by phocine distemper virus.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Many other viruses, including caliciviruses, herpesviruses, adenoviruses and parvoviruses, circulate in marine mammal populations.
[src:virology/virus-p02] In December 2022, scientists reported the first observation of virovory via an experiment on pond water containing chlorovirus, which commonly infects green algae in freshwater environments.
[src:virology/virus-p02] When all other microbial food sources were removed from the water, the ciliate Halteria was observed to have increased in number due to the active consumption of chlorovirus as a food source instead of its typical bacterivore diet.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses are an important natural means of transferring genes between different species, which increases genetic diversity and drives evolution.
[src:virology/virus-p02] It is thought that viruses played a central role in early evolution, before the diversification of the last universal common ancestor into bacteria, archaea and eukaryotes.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses are still one of the largest reservoirs of unexplored genetic diversity on Earth.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses are important to the study of molecular and cell biology as they provide simple systems that can be used to manipulate and investigate the functions of cells.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The study and use of viruses have provided valuable information about aspects of cell biology.
[src:virology/virus-p02] For example, viruses have been useful in the study of genetics and helped our understanding of the basic mechanisms of molecular genetics, such as DNA replication, transcription, RNA processing, translation, protein transport, and immunology.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Geneticists often use viruses as vectors to introduce genes into cells that they are studying.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This is useful for making the cell produce a foreign substance, or to study the effect of introducing a new gene into the genome.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Similarly, virotherapy uses viruses as vectors to treat various diseases, as they can specifically target cells and DNA.
[src:virology/virus-p02] It shows promising use in the treatment of cancer and in gene therapy.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Eastern European scientists have used phage therapy as an alternative to antibiotics for some time, and interest in this approach is increasing, because of the high level of antibiotic resistance now found in some pathogenic bacteria.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The expression of heterologous proteins by viruses is the basis of several manufacturing processes that are currently being used for the production of various proteins such as vaccine antigens and antibodies.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Industrial processes have been recently developed using viral vectors and several pharmaceutical proteins are currently in pre-clinical and clinical trials.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Virotherapy involves the use of genetically modified viruses to treat diseases.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses have been modified by scientists to reproduce in cancer cells and destroy them but not infect healthy cells.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Talimogene laherparepvec (T-VEC), for example, is a modified herpes simplex virus that has had a gene, which is required for viruses to replicate in healthy cells, deleted and replaced with a human gene (GM-CSF) that stimulates immunity.
[src:virology/virus-p02] When this virus infects cancer cells, it destroys them and in doing so the presence of GM-CSF gene attracts dendritic cells from the surrounding tissues of the body.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The dendritic cells process the dead cancer cells and present components of them to other cells of the immune system.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Having completed successful clinical trials, the virus gained approval for the treatment of melanoma in late 2015.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Viruses that have been reprogrammed to kill cancer cells are called oncolytic viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] From the viewpoint of a materials scientist, viruses can be regarded as organic nanoparticles.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Their surface carries specific tools that enable them to cross the barriers of their host cells.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The size and shape of viruses and the number and nature of the functional groups on their surface are precisely defined.
[src:virology/virus-p02] As such, viruses are commonly used in materials science as scaffolds for covalently linked surface modifications.
[src:virology/virus-p02] A particular quality of viruses is that they can be tailored by directed evolution.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The powerful techniques developed by life sciences are becoming the basis of engineering approaches towards nanomaterials, opening a wide range of applications far beyond biology and medicine.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Because of their size, shape, and well-defined chemical structures, viruses have been used as templates for organising materials on the nanoscale.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Examples include the work at the Naval Research Laboratory in Washington, D.C., using Cowpea mosaic virus (CPMV) particles to amplify signals in DNA microarray based sensors.
[src:virology/virus-p02] In this application, the virus particles separate the fluorescent dyes used for signalling to prevent the formation of non-fluorescent dimers that act as quenchers.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Another example is the use of CPMV as a nanoscale breadboard for molecular electronics.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Many viruses can be synthesised de novo ("from scratch").
[src:virology/virus-p02] The first synthetic virus was created in 2002.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Although somewhat of a misconception, it is not the actual virus that is synthesised, but rather its DNA genome (in case of a DNA virus), or a cDNA copy of its genome (in case of RNA viruses).
[src:virology/virus-p02] For many virus families the naked synthetic DNA or RNA (once enzymatically converted back from the synthetic cDNA) is infectious when introduced into a cell.
[src:virology/virus-p02] That is, they contain all the necessary information to produce new viruses.
[src:virology/virus-p02] This technology is now being used to investigate novel vaccine strategies.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The ability to synthesise viruses has far-reaching consequences, since viruses can no longer be regarded as extinct, as long as the information of their genome sequence is known and permissive cells are available.
[src:virology/virus-p02] As of June 2021, the full-length genome sequences of 11,464 different viruses, including smallpox, are publicly available in an online database maintained by the National Institutes of Health.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The ability of viruses to cause devastating epidemics in human societies has led to the concern that viruses could be weaponised for biological warfare.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Further concern was raised by the successful recreation of the infamous 1918 influenza virus in a laboratory.
[src:virology/virus-p02] The smallpox virus devastated numerous societies throughout history before its eradication.
[src:virology/virus-p02] There are only two centres in the world authorised by the WHO to keep stocks of smallpox virus: the State Research Center of Virology and Biotechnology VECTOR in Russia and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in the United States.
[src:virology/virus-p02] It may be used as a weapon, as the vaccine for smallpox sometimes had severe side-effects, it is no longer used routinely in any country.
[src:virology/virus-p02] Thus, much of the modern human population has almost no established resistance to smallpox and would be vulnerable to the virus.
